/www.youtube.com/watch?v=eyhV83j9zJI|title=Drag Queens try french \"Andouillette\" (w/ Latrice Royale, Kim Chi) {{!}} Pardon my french food #2 {{!}} VF|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=July 15, 2018|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Werq The World''\n|Herself\n|Featured Queen\n|}\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" <!-- Do not center -->\n|- <!-- Never add unnecessary background colors -->\n! Year\n! Award Giving Body\n! Category\n! Work\n! Results\n! Ref.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|2020\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Queerty|The Queerties]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|Drag Royalty\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|Herself\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/Queerties2020/|title='The 2020 Queerties|work=Cheat Sheet|date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{RuPaul's Drag Race}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royale, Latrice}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American drag queens]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT African Americans]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Compton, California]]\n[[Category:RuPaul's Drag Race contestants|Latrice Royale]]\n[[Category:RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars contestants]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "- space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latrice_Royale"}
{"title_page": "Pat McCarran", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Pat McCarran\n| image name = Nevada Senator. Washington, D.C., April 24. A new informal picture of Senator Pat McCarran, democrat of Nevada LCCN2016875505 (cropped).jpg\n| jr/sr1 = United States Senator\n| state1 = [[Nevada]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| term_start1 = March 4, 1933\n| term_end1 = September 28, 1954\n| preceded1 = [[Tasker Oddie]]\n| succeeded1 = [[Ernest S. Brown]]\n| office2 = Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]]\n| term2 = January 2, 1917 \u2013 January 4, 1919\n| preceded2 = [[Frank Herbert Norcross]]\n| succeeded2 =[[Benjamin Wilson Coleman]]\n| office3 = Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]]\n| term3 = January 2, 1913 \u2013 January 1, 1917\n| preceded3 = [[James G. Sweeney]]\n| succeeded3 =[[Edward Augustus Ducker]]\n| office4 = [[District Attorney]] of [[Nye County, Nevada]]\n| term_start4 = 1907\n| term_end4 = 1909\n| predecessor4 = W. B Pittman\n| successor4 = Cleve H. Baker\n| office5 = Member of the [[Nevada Assembly]] from [[Washoe County, Nevada|Washoe County]]\n| term_start5 = 1903\n| term_end5 = 1905\n| alongside5 = Peter Burke; W. D. R. Graham, H. R. Cooke, A. D. Graham, J. F. Crosby, J. E. Soucherau\n| predecessor5 = Phil Jacobs, G. E. Peckham, W. W. Webster\n| successor5 = Walter Hastings, A. W. Holmes, E. R. Dodge, R. H. Kinney, J. W. Wright, J. S. Orr\n| birth_name = Patrick Anthony McCarran\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1876|8|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Reno, Nevada]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1954|9|28|1876|8|8}}\n| death_place = [[Hawthorne, Nevada]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Mountain View Cemetery, Reno, Nevada\n| profession= Lawyer\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Anthony McCarran''' (August 8, 1876 \u2013 September 28, 1954) was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from [[History of Nevada|Nevada]] from 1933 until 1954.  McCarran was born in [[Reno, Nevada]], attended [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada State University]], and was a farmer and rancher.  In 1902 he won election to the [[Nevada Assembly]], but in 1904 he was an unsuccessful candidate for the [[Nevada State Senate]].  He completed private law studies and was admitted to the bar in 1905; in 1906 he won election as [[Nye County, Nevada|Nye County]]'s [[district attorney]]. He served a two-year term, after which he relocated to Reno.\n\nFrom 1913 to 1917, McCarran was an associate justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]], and he served as chief justice from 1917 to 1919.  In 1932 McCarran defeated Republican incumbent [[Tasker Oddie]] for [[List of United States Senators from Nevada|Nevada's Class 3 Senate seat]] to become the state's first U.S. Senator born in Nevada; he was reelected three times, and served from 1933 until his death. In his Senate career, McCarran served as chairman of the District of Columbia, Judiciary, and Joint Foreign Economic Cooperation Committees. He died in [[Hawthorne, Nevada]] and was buried at Mountain View Cemetery in Reno. [[McCarran International Airport]] in [[Las Vegas]] was later named in his honor.\n\nMcCarran is remembered as one of the few Democrats to reject the [[New Deal]]. In addition, he was a proponent of the aviation industry; he was a sponsor of the [[Civil Aeronautics Act]] of 1938, and was a proponent of establishing the [[United States Air Force]] as a separate entity from the [[United States Army|Army]]. McCarran was also an ardent anti-Communist, to the point of supporting fascists including [[Francisco Franco]] as a way to prevent its spread, and sponsored the [[McCarran Act]], otherwise known as the [[Subversive Activities Control Act of 1950]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMcCarran was born in [[Reno, Nevada]], the child of [[Irish American|Irish immigrants]] Margaret Shay and Patrick McCarran.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Browne|first1=Blaine Terry|last2=Cottrell |first2=Robert C.|date=2010|title=Lives and Times - Individuals and Issues in American History Since 1865|url=https://archive.org/details/livestimesindivi0000brow|url-access=registration|location=Lanham, MD|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|page=[https://archive.org/details/livestimesindivi0000brow/page/173 173]|isbn=978-0-7425-6193-9}}</ref>  He was educated in Reno and in 1897, he graduated as [[valedictorian]] of his class at [[Reno High School]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\">{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Jerome E.|date=1982|title=Pat McCarran, Political Boss of Nevada|url=https://archive.org/details/patmccarranpolit0000edwa|url-access=registration|location=Reno, NV|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-071-9}}</ref>{{rp|[https://archive.org/details/patmccarranpolit0000edwa/page/3 3]\u20134, 7}} McCarran's mother was a devout Catholic, and he inherited his mother's faith.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|1-2}}\n\nHe attended the [[University of Nevada, Reno]], but withdrew to work on the family sheep ranch when his father suffered an injury.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> He [[reading law|studied law]] with [[William Woodburn]], and served in the [[Nevada Assembly]] from 1903 to 1905.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> In 1904 he was an unsuccessful candidate for the [[Nevada State Senate]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1905, and in 1906 he was elected [[district attorney]] of [[Nye County, Nevada|Nye County]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> He served one term, 1907 to 1909, after which he moved to Reno to continue practicing law.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>\n\nSome sources incorrectly state that McCarran received a bachelor's degree in 1901 and a master's degree in 1915.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rocha|first=Guy|date=May 2001|title= Myth #64: Getting the Facts Down Pat|url=http://nsla.nv.gov/Archives/Myths/Getting_the_Facts_Down_Pat/ |location=Carson City|publisher=Nevada State Library and Archives|page=1}}</ref> In fact, he did not receive a bachelor's degree at all, and the [[master of arts]] he received from [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada State University]] in 1915 was an [[honorary degree]].<ref>{{cite book|last=University of Nevada|date=November 1, 1922|title=Quarterly Bulletin|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3xXOAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA37&dq=mccarran+%22university+of+nevada%22+%22M.A.%22+1915#v=onepage&q=mccarran%20%22university%20of%20nevada%22%20%22M.A.%22%201915&f=false|location=Reno, NV|publisher=University of Nevada|page=33}}</ref> He also received an honorary [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from [[Georgetown University]] in 1943,<ref>{{cite news|title=Georgetown U. to Confer Degree on Senator M'Carran|work= The Guardian (Little Rock)|page=5|date=September 10, 1943|url=http://arc.stparchive.com/Archive/ARC/ARC09101943p05.php}}</ref> and an honorary [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from the University of Nevada in 1945.<ref>{{cite book|last=University of Nevada Board of Regents|date=1946|title=Biennial Report of the Board of Regents of the State University of Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/?id=y2RMAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22mccarran%22+%22nevada%22+%22ll.d.%22+1945&q=mccarran|location=Reno|publisher=University of Nevada|page=21}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career==\nIn 1912, McCarran was elected to the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]], succeeding John G. Sweeney.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis |first=Sam Post|date=1913|title=The History of Nevada|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebcUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA306|location=Reno, NV|publisher=Elms Publishing Co.|page=306}}</ref> He served as an Associate Justice from January 1913 to January 1917.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\">{{cite news|date=January 2, 1917|title=M'Carran Is New Chief Justice|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/147917797|newspaper=Reno Gazette-Journal|location=Reno, NV|page=3|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn January 1917, he succeeded [[Frank Herbert Norcross]] as Chief Justice.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 12, 1917 |title=Judge McCarran Chosen Chief Justice of Court |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/375520722/ |work=The Pioche Record |location=Pioche, NV |page=1 |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1918,<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/> and served until January 1919, when he was succeeded on the court by Edward Augustus Ducker, and as Chief Justice by Benjamin Wilson Coleman.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/>\n\nBoth during his time on the court and afterwards, McCarran continued to play a central role in Nevada's state government, as well as its legal and criminal justice systems. From 1913 to 1918, he served on the state Board of Library Commissioners.<ref>{{cite book|date=1955|title=United States Code Congressional and Administrative News|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Kus0AQAAIAAJ&dq=%22mccarran%22+%22nevada%22+%22library+commission%22+1913+1918&q=%22library+commission%22|publisher=West Publishing Company|location=Eagan, Minnesota|page=42}}</ref> In addition, he served as chairman of the [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada State University]] Board of Visitors.<ref>{{cite book|last=Farnsworth|first=Joe|date=1917|title=List of Members, Officers and Committees and Rules of the Two Houses of the Nevada Legislature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0h8uAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA8|location=Carson City, NV|publisher=State Printing Company|page=8}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1913 to 1919 he served on the state Board of Pardons.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia of Nevada\">{{cite book|date=2000|title=Encyclopedia of Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oLd4nCEMbpUC&pg=PA194|location=Santa Barbara, CA|publisher=Somerset Publishers, Inc.|page=194|isbn=978-0-403-09611-4|ref={{sfnRef|''Encyclopedia of Nevada''}}}}</ref> He was a member of the Board of Parole Commissioners from 1913 to 1918, and he served on the Board of Bar Examiners from 1919 until 1932.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia of Nevada\"/>\n\nMcCarran was president of the Nevada Bar Association from 1920 to 1921, and was a vice president of the [[American Bar Association]] from 1922 to 1923.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCarran|first=Pat|date=May 1, 1939|title=My Views on Senate Bill 1635|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cz9AxBg8l_wC&pg=RA1-PA36|journal=Popular Aviation|location=Chicago, Illinois|publisher=Ziff-Davis Publishing Company|page=36}}</ref>\n\n==United States Senate==\n===Election history===\nMcCarran's ambition to serve as a U.S. Senator was well known in Nevada, and often the subject of jokes in the press. He ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic nomination in 1916, and lost to incumbent [[Key Pittman]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rothman|first=Hal|date=2010|title=The Making of Modern Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YzgOWKpnBGcC&pg=PA79|location=Reno, NV|publisher=University of Nevada Press|page=79|isbn=978-0-87417-826-5}}</ref> McCarran endorsed Pittman in the general election, and Pittman was reelected.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/>\n\nIn 1926, McCarran was again a candidate for the U.S. Senate. He lost the Democratic nomination to [[Raymond T. Baker]], who was defeated by Republican incumbent [[Tasker Oddie]] in the general election.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/>\n\nIn 1932, McCarran was the Democratic nominee, and he defeated Oddie in the general election.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/> He was reelected in [[United States Senate elections, 1938|1938]], [[United States Senate elections, 1944|1944]], and [[United States Senate elections, 1950|1950]], and served from March 4, 1933 until his death.<ref name=Late_a_Senator>{{cite book|date=1955|title=Patrick Anthony McCarran, Late a Senator from Nevada|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015002677295;view=1up;seq=11|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=US Government Printing Office|page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Leadership positions===\nDuring his career as a Senator, McCarran served as chairman of the: [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Columbia|Committee on the District of Columbia]] ([[77th United States Congress|77th]] and [[78th United States Congress|78th]] Congresses); [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]] ([[78th United States Congress|78th]], [[79th United States Congress|79th]], [[81st United States Congress|81st]], and [[82nd United States Congress|82nd]] Congresses); and [[List of defunct United States congressional committees#Defunct Joint Committees|Joint Committee on Foreign Economic Cooperation]] ([[81st United States Congress]]) (co-chairman).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000308|title=Patrick Anthony McCarran profile|last=Historian of the United States Senate|website=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|publisher=United States Senate|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition to Roosevelt administration===\nDuring his first term as senator, McCarran was engaged in a major struggle for the control of patronage appointments relating to federal projects in Nevada with his fellow Democratic Senator, [[Key Pittman]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69}} As Nevada was a poor state badly hit by the Great Depression, there was considerable competition to be awarded a patronage appointment, and those who had control of patronage were in a strong position politically. As Pittman was the senior senator, and McCarran only a freshman senator, President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] tended to side with Pittman in the struggle for the control of patronage, thus earning McCarran's enmity.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70}} Much of McCarran's opposition to the New Deal stemmed from his anger and spite that Pittman was able to make more patronage appointments relating to New Deal projects in Nevada than he was.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70}} Pittman's increasing serious drinking problems rendered him somewhat ineffective in his last years, and McCarran was able to gradually take over the Democratic Party in Nevada, becoming the dominant force within the Nevada Democrats by 1938.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70, 74}}\n\nDespite being a Democrat, beginning in the late 1930s McCarran came into increasing opposition with Roosevelt, believing that Roosevelt's \"second\" New Deal policies following his 1936 reelection were too liberal.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} Further complicating the picture was that by 1939, Roosevelt was convinced that the Danzig crisis would probably lead to a war in Europe, and that it was in the best interests of the United States to ensure that Britain and France defeated Germany, which would require relaxing the various Neutrality Acts passed by Congress earlier in the 1930s. As Pittman was chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, his co-operation was essential. Thus for foreign policy reasons, Roosevelt had to back Pittman despite the way he was losing control of the Nevada Democrats to McCarran.  From 1939 to 1941, the isolationist McCarran opposed Roosevelt's foreign policy of aiding the Allies, accusing the president of trying to involve America in a war that not its business.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} In particular, the Catholic conservative McCarran was outraged by the decision of the Roosevelt administration to offer military and economic aid to the Soviet Union in the summer of 1941, arguing that it was immoral to assist the \"godless communists\".<ref name=\"auto3\">Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 271</ref> In a speech on the Senate floor, McCarran declared that \"I despise Mr. Hitler and all that he stands for, and equally I despise Mr. Stalin and all that he stands for\", before going on to argue that through he did not like Nazi Germany that he regarded the Third Reich as the lesser evil compared to the Soviet Union, and felt it was profoundly wrong for the United States to offer aid to the nation he felt was the greater evil.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> McCarran was greatly influenced by a statement from the Catholic Church in the spring of 1937 declaring that \"Communism is intrinsically wrong, and no one who would save Christian civilization may collaborate with it in any undertaking\".<ref name=\"auto3\"/> McCarran supported the war effort after the United States entered the conflict following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor.\n\nMcCarran's positions on several key committees, most notably Appropriations and Judiciary, gave him significant influence that he used to obtain federal funding for Nevada, a fact which contributed substantially to his home state popularity.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|122-123}} In 1944, McCarran was challenged by [[Vail M. Pittman]] in the Democratic primary, leading to an especially hard-fought campaign that was finally won by McCarran.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|119}} At the time, Pittman explained his loss as due to McCarran's ability to bring federal money to fund infrastructure projects in Nevada, at the time a relatively backward state, saying: <blockquote>\"McCarran had a pet project in nearly every town in the state. Housing projects, sewage systems, airfields, power projects, school houses and heaven knows what...People remember the little personal favors and the things that help financially, but they forgot all the things done that are more remote, but more vital\".<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|119}}</blockquote> McCarran's biographer, Jerome Edwards, endorsed this theory, arguing that the narrow margin of McCarran's victory over Pittman in the Democratic primary suggests that a substantial number of registered Democrats in Nevada were dissatisfied with him, but his ability to have the federal government built infrastructure projects that Nevada could not afford on its own explains his enduring appeal in his state.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|119}} Outside of Nevada, McCarran had the reputation of a narrow-minded and parochial  senator who put the interests of Nevada ahead of the wider national interests; the same reasons that made him unpopular outside of Nevada made him popular there as he had the reputation of a dogged, relentless fighter for Nevada's interests.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} McCarran's repeatedly attempted via filibusters to force the federal government to stockpile silver, a measure that would have benefited Nevada where silver mining was a major industry, but was widely denounced outside of Nevada as a plan for wasteful spending designed only to benefit his state.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} After Pearl Harbor, McCarran in his speeches to the Senate made much of the fact that most of American industry was concentrated in the Northeast and the Midwest, and argued that the federal government had the duty to ensure that war production was shifted to less industrialized states like Nevada.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94-95}}\n\nMcCarran also was well known for his efforts to help constituents with any problems that they might have with the federal government, often going to extraordinary lengths.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|122-124}} For instance, when a teenager from Nevada stolen 150 volumes from the [[Library of Congress]] and mutilated hundreds of more books, his parents asked McCarran to intervene to ensure that their son was not prosecuted.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|123}} McCarran duly called up the Washington D.C. District Attorney  [[Edward Curran]] and the FBI director, [[J. Edgar Hoover]], saying he not want the teenager prosecuted as that would cost him the votes of the parents of the bibliophobic vandal-thief, and owing to the senator's advocacy, the teenager was not prosecuted despite the overwhelming evidence of his guilt and his theft and destruction of books costing thousands of dollars.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|1234}} in 1942, when a Reno couple learned that their son had been captured by the Japanese at Wake Island, they appealed to McCarran for help.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|123}} McCarran brought considerable pressure to bear on the State Department to set up a prisoner exchange, saying that it essential for him to keep the two votes of the parents of the POW, through the State Department insisted that the United States was not in the business of prisoner exchanges, which would involve making deals with the Axis powers that the American people would find unsavory.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|124-125}}\n\nIn the 1940s-50s, 40% of Senate bills had to first be approved by the Senate Judiciary committee, giving McCarran immense power as he could easily \"kill\" these bills in his committee<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}}<ref name=\"auto1\">Oshinksy, David ''A Conspiracy So Immense'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005 page 207.</ref> Other committee chairmen had the same powers over bills related to their fields, but the number of bills that had to passed by the Judiciary Committee made McCarran far more influential than the other senate committee chairmen.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Over time, McCarran used his position as chairman of the Judiciary Committee to engage in much deal-making that allowed him to collect a significant number of political \"debts\", making him of the most powerful Senators.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70}} McCarran's conservative politics, which pitted him against first Roosevelt and then Truman, frequently led to the question being asked why he continue to sit as a Democrat instead of defecting over to the Republicans. In 1950, when McCarran asked that question by a reporter, he responded: \"I can do more good by staying in the Democratic Party and watching the lunatic fringe-the Roosevelt crowd\".<ref name=\"auto\">Oshinksy, David ''A Conspiracy So Immense'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005 page 208.</ref> McCarran was against the plans of the Roosevelt-Truman administrations for federal health insurance and increased education spending; favored restricting the power of unions; was opposed to increased immigration, saying he did not want \"undesirables from abroad\" coming to America; and was against the United Nations, which he called \"a haven for spies and Communists\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> As chairman of the Judiciary Committee, he appointed his friend, Senator [[James Eastland]], a well known white supremacist and segregationist, as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Civil Rights.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Such was McCarran's power that in July 1952, the liberal ''Washington Post'' newspaper (which was not friendly to the conservative McCarran) declared in an article: \"It sums the character of this congress to state an unquestionable fact: that its most important member was Patrick A. McCarran\".<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|122-147}}\n\n===Aviation advocate===\nMcCarran sponsored numerous laws concerning the early commercial aviation industry, including the [[Civil Aeronautics Act]] of 1938 and the Federal Airport Act of 1945.<ref name=\"Late_a_Senator\"/> He was an early advocate of the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] as a military component separate from the Army, and began sponsoring the necessary legislation in 1933.<ref name=\"shaped\">[http://www.1st100.com/part2/mccarran.html The First 100 Persons Who Shaped Southern Nevada], 1st100.com; accessed December 12, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Other initiatives===\nIn 1945, McCarran co-sponsored the [[McCarran-Ferguson Act]], which exempted the insurance industry from most federal regulations, including [[Antitrust law|antitrust]] rules.  Instead, this act required states to regulate insurance, including mandatory licensing requirements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statefarm.com/about-us/company-overview/company-profile/insurance-industry-issues/the-mccarran-ferguson-act|title=What is the McCarran-Ferguson Act?|website=Company Overview: McCarran-Ferguson Act|publisher=State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company|location=Bloomington, IL|access-date=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMcCarran also co-sponsored the 1946 [[Administrative Procedure Act (United States)|Administrative Procedures Act]], which required federal agencies to keep the public informed of their organizational structure, procedures and rules, allowed for public participation in the rule making process, and established uniform standards for the conduct of formal rule making.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grisinger|first=Joanna L.|date=2012|title=The Unwieldy American State: Administrative Politics since the New Deal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GU0gAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA77|location=New York, NY|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=77|isbn=978-1-107-00432-0}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-communist===\n[[File:Pat McCarran (Nevada) (1947).jpg|thumb|[[Harris & Ewing photo studio|Harris & Ewing]] portrait of McCarran in 1947]]\nMcCarran established himself as one of the Senate's most ardent anti-Communists.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ceplair|first=Larry|date=2011|title=Anti-communism in Twentieth-century America: A Critical History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pNAKcnXoMCgC&pg=PA97|location=Santa Barbara, CA|publisher=ABC CLIO|page=97|isbn=978-1-4408-0047-4}}</ref> An admirer of Spanish dictator [[Francisco Franco]], he was nicknamed the \"Senator from Madrid\" by columnist [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]] over his efforts to increase [[foreign aid]] to Spain.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carter|first1=Ralph G.|last2=Scott|first2=James M.|date=2009|title=Choosing to Lead: Understanding Congressional Foreign Policy Entrepreneurs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYzGTelSjcsC&pg=PA89|location=Durham, NC|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=89\u201390|isbn=978-0-8223-4503-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ybarra|first=Michael J.|date=2004|title=Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mVl3AAAAMAAJ&dq=mccarran+pearson+%22senator+from+madrid%22&q=%22senator+from+madrid%22|location=Hanover, NH|publisher=Steerforth Press|page=504|isbn=978-1-58642-065-9}}</ref> McCarran voted for President [[Harry S. Truman]]'s 1947 plan to provide aid to Greece and Turkey as part of an effort to prevent them from becoming communist, but in 1949 McCarran broke with Truman after he rejected McCarran's request for increased economic aid to Spain and military aid to [[Chiang Kai-shek]]'s nationalist Chinese government.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|132}} In 1949, McCarran visited Spain, where he was treated like a visiting head of state, and he made it clear his admiration for ''El Caudillo'' (\"the leader\") as Franco had styled himself in imitation of Mussolini and Hitler.<ref>Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 pages 473-474</ref> McCarran's praise for Franco, who had leaned in a pro-Axis neutrality for much of World War II, greatly annoyed Truman who told the press that: \"I don't like Franco and I never will\".<ref>Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 474</ref> During his visit to Spain, McCarran met with Franco to discuss U.S aid for his regime, which infuriated Truman who noted that the constitution gave the executive the right to conduct foreign policy, which led him to angrily declare that the senator from Nevada did not have the right to conduct his own foreign policy.<ref>Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 475</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], McCarran continued his anti-Communist efforts. He was a supporter of [[Chiang Kai-shek]], whose \"[[loss of China]]\" to communists in 1949 he blamed on Soviet influence in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Leffler|first=Melvyn P.|date=1992|title=A Preponderance of Power: National Security, the Truman Administration, and the Cold War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pIIeG_yn72wC&pg=PA295|location=Stanford, CA|publisher=Stanford University Press|page=295|isbn=9780804722186}}</ref> In 1952, McCarran attended a dinner hosted by the [[Kuomintang]] Chinese Ambassador to Washington together with Republican Senators [[Joseph McCarthy]] and [[William Knowland]]; the event began with the toast \"Back to the mainland!\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gillon|first1=Steven M.|last2=Kunz|first2=Diane B.|date=1993|title=America During the Cold War|url=https://books.google.com/?id=e4QaAQAAIAAJ&dq=mccarran+%22back+to+the+mainland%22&q=%22back+to+the+mainland%22|location=San Diego, CA|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|page=58|isbn=9780155004153}}</ref> McCarthy sought McCarran's favor after he started his \"crusade against Communism\", giving \"hot tips\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> McCarran told his friends that \"Joe is a bit irresponsible\" and a \"publicity hound\", but praised him for his attacks on the Truman administration.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 1951, in an interview with the ''U.S. News'', McCarran replied to the questions asked that he believed that the American Communist Party had been engaging in the \"infiltration\" of the media, churches, university faculties, unions and \"nationality groups\".<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn August\u2013September 1950, McCarran was the chief sponsor of the [[McCarran Internal Security Act]]. This legislation required the [[Communist Party USA]] and affiliated organizations to register with the [[Attorney General of the United States|Attorney General]] and established the [[Subversive Activities Control Board]] to investigate possible communist subversion and communist front organizations. The act also gave the government the power to imprison without trial of people \"likely\" to be spies, saboteurs, and \"subversives\" if the president declared a national emergency, through those imprisoned could appeal to a review board.<ref name=\"auto4\">Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 117.</ref> President [[Harry S. Truman]] vetoed the act, charging that it violated civil liberties and put the government in \"the business of thought control\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/> In the \"hot summer\" of 1950, with the [[Korean War]] raging abroad and the [[Red Scare#Second Red Scare (1947\u201360)|Second Red Scare]] at home, few in Congress wanted to be appear \"soft\" on communism, and Congress overrode Truman's veto, with the House voting 248 to 48 and the Senate 57 to 10, forcing Truman to reluctantly enforce a law he felt violated the Bill of Rights.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> After passage of the act, the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] built six concentration camps (either old POW camps from World War II or abandoned military bases) to hold \"subversives\" if a national emergency was declared.<ref name=\"auto6\">Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 118.</ref> No such emergency was ever declared and the camps were never used before being shut down in 1957 as a cost-cutting measure.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Due to numerous hearings, delays and [[appeal]]s, the act was never enforced, and its major provisions were declared unconstitutional by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in 1965 and 1967.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fried|first=Richard M.|year=1990|title=Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=187|isbn=0-19-504361-8}}</ref>\n\nAs chairman of the Judiciary Committee, McCarran created and was the first chairman of the [[Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]] that investigated the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[Harry S. Truman]] administrations to expose supposed communist spies and sympathizers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Black|first=James Eric|date=2016|title=Walt Kelly and Pogo: The Art of the Political Swamp|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=umlECwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|location=Jefferson, NC|publisher=McFarland & Company|page=199|isbn=978-0-7864-7987-0}}</ref> In 1951, subcommittee investigators seized the records of the [[Institute of Pacific Relations]] in an effort to identify alleged communist infiltration of the organization, which had been formed in 1925 to foster cooperation between Pacific Rim nations.<ref>{{cite book|last=Newman|first=Robert P.|title=Owen Lattimore and the \"loss\" of China|url=https://archive.org/details/owenlattimorelos0000newm|url-access=registration|location=Berkeley, CA|publisher=University of California Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/owenlattimorelos0000newm/page/318 318]|isbn=978-0-520-07388-3|date=March 2, 1992}}</ref>  McCarran made much of these records when questioning a [[Sinologist]], [[Owen Lattimore]], in acrimonious hearings over 12 days in February 1951.<ref name=\"auto11\">Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 148</ref> In March 1950, Senator McCarthy accused Lattimore of being the \"top Russian agent\" responsible for the \"loss of China\", thereby making Lattimore, a previously little known expert on China, into an internationally famous figure. During the hearings, it became quickly apparent that McCarran and Lattimore deeply disliked each other with the two men frequently engaging in shouting matches and interrupting one another.<ref name=\"auto12\">Oshinksy, David ''A Conspiracy So Immense'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005 page 209.</ref> When it was established that Lattimore had met President Truman in 1945 to discuss America's China policy, McCarran sarcastically commented: \"He visited the President once and forgot it\".<ref name=\"auto11\"/> McCarran demanded that Lattimore prove a negative, asking him \"can you say that the IPR and you had no influence on upon the Far Eastern experts in the State Department?\"<ref name=\"auto11\"/> McCarran worked to establish that Lattimore was the man responsible for the \"loss of China\", claiming General [[George Marshall]]'s policy during his 1945 to 1947 diplomatic mission to China during that country's civil war between nationalists and communists as being \"substantially the same\" as that recommended by Lattimore.<ref name=\"auto11\"/> At the end of the hearings, McCarran gave Lattimore what was described as a \"tongue lashing\", stating he was \"so flagrantly defiant\" and \"so persistent in his efforts to confuse and obscure the facts that the committee feels constrained to take due notice of his conduct...That he has uttered untruths stands clear in the record\".<ref name=\"auto11\"/> The report of the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee written by McCarran concluded that China was indeed \"lost\" because of the policy followed by the State Department, declaring: \"Owen Lattimore and John Carter Vincent were influential in bringing about a change in United States policy...favorable to the Chinese Communists\".<ref name=\"auto12\"/> Through McCarran was careful not to call Lattimore a Soviet spy in his report, which would have allowed him to sue for libel, he came very close with the statement: \"Owen Lattimore was, from some time beginning in the 1930s, a conscious, articulate instrument of the Soviet conspiracy\".<ref name=\"auto12\"/>\n\nMcCarran subsequently pushed successfully for Lattimore to be [[indictment|indicted]] for [[perjury]]. As chairman of the Judiciary Committee, he held up the nomination of Truman's nominee for Attorney General, [[James McGranery]], until McGanery promised to indict Lattimore.<ref>Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 149.</ref> Lattimore's lawyer [[Abe Fortas]] defended him by claiming McCarran had deliberately asked questions about arcane and obscure matters that took place in the 1930s in the hope that Lattimore would not be able to recall them properly, thereby giving grounds for perjury indictments. Federal Judge [[Luther Youngdahl]] later dismissed all seven charges against Lattimore on the grounds that the matters in question were insubstantial, of little concern to McCarran's inquiry, or the result of questions phrased in such a way that they could not be fairly answered.<ref>Haynes & Klehr ''Early Cold War Spies''; p. 47; US Senate, 82nd Congress, 2nd Session, Committee on the Judiciary, Institute of Pacific Relations, Report No. 2050, p. 224</ref>\n\nOn 27 July 1953, the [[Korean Armistice Agreement|armistice of Panmunjom]] was signed ending the Korean War. McCarran attracted national attention when he criticized President Dwight Eisenhower on the Senate floor for signing the armistice, which he called \"a perpetuation of a fraud on this country and the United Nations\".<ref name=\"auto7\">Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 714</ref> McCarran believed that the United States and the rest of its allies fighting under the united Nations banner in Korea should have fought on until all of Korea was unified under the leadership of President [[Syngman Rhee]], which led him to see the armistice as a sort of American defeat.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\n===Changes to immigration law===\nIn June 1952, McCarran joined [[Francis Walter]] in sponsorship of the [[McCarran&ndash;Walter Act]], a law that abolished racial restrictions found in United States immigration and naturalization statutes going back to the Naturalization Act of 1790 and also imposed more rigid restrictions on quotas for immigrants entering the United States. It also stiffened the existing law relating to the admission, exclusion and deportation of dangerous aliens (as defined by the McCarran Internal Security Act). In response to the act he made a well known statement:\n\n{{quote|I believe that this nation is the last hope of Western civilization and if this oasis of the world shall be overrun, perverted, contaminated or destroyed, then the last flickering light of humanity will be extinguished. I take no issue with those who would praise the contributions which have been made to our society by people of many races, of varied creeds and colors. America is indeed a joining together of many streams which go to form a mighty river which we call the American way. However, we have in the United States today hard-core, indigestible blocs which have not become integrated into the American way of life, but which, on the contrary are its deadly enemies. Today, as never before, untold millions are storming our gates for admission and those gates are cracking under the strain. The solution of the problems of Europe and Asia will not come through a transplanting of those problems en masse to the United States.... I do not intend to become prophetic, but if the enemies of this legislation succeed in riddling it to pieces, or in amending it beyond recognition, they will have contributed more to promote this nation's downfall than any other group since we achieved our independence as a nation.<ref>Senator Pat McCarran, Congressional Record, March 2, 1953, p. 1518</ref>}}\n\nSome of the immigration provisions of the act were later superseded by the [[1965 Immigration Act]], but the power of the government to deny visas for ideological reasons remained on the books another 25 years after that.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holmes |first=Steven A. |date=February 2, 1990 |title=Legislation Eases Limits on Aliens |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/02/us/legislation-eases-limits-on-aliens.html |work=New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\n==Death and burial==\nMcCarran died in [[Hawthorne, Nevada]] on September 28, 1954, shortly after leaving the stage following a speech he gave at a political rally.<ref name=\"Late_a_Senator\"/><ref name=Dies>{{cite news |last=Sun Staff |date=September 29, 1954 |title=McCarran Dies: Senator Collapses After Speaking to Hawthorne Demo |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1954/sep/29/mccarran-dies/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |location=Las Vegas, NV}}</ref>  According to news accounts published after his death, McCarran suffered a fatal heart attack, after having recovered from attacks in 1951 and 1953.<ref name=\"Dies\"/> McCarran was buried at Mountain View Cemetery in Reno.<ref>{{cite book |last=U.S. Congress |author-link= |date=August 6, 1959 |title=Report: Acceptance of Statue of Patrick A. McCarran |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0s0jAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA27-PA7 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=US Government Printing Office |page=7 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1903, McCarran married Harriet Martha \"Birdie\" Weeks (1882-1963).<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=Margaret>{{cite magazine |last=McCarran |first=Margaret Patricia |date=Fall-Winter 1968 |title=Patrick Anthony McCarran, 1876-1954 |url=http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210777-1968-3-4Fall-Winter.pdf |magazine=Nevada Historical Society Quarterly |location=Reno, NV |publisher=Nevada Historical Society |pages=5\u201353}}</ref>  They were the parents of four daughters and one son.<ref name=\"Dies\"/>  Samuel McCarran became a doctor and worked in Reno.<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>  Margaret and Mary became members of the [[Dominican Order#Sisters|Order of Dominican Sisters]].<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>  Norine was a longtime employee of the Library of Congress.<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>  Patricia became the wife of Edwin Parry Hay of Maryland.<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nMcCarran is remembered as one of the few Democrats to oppose President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and reject the [[New Deal]].<ref name=Pederson>{{cite book |last=Pederson |first=William D. |date=2006 |title=The FDR Years |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cv-kRJoXag4C&pg=PA177 |location=Facts on File |publisher=New York, NY |page=177 |isbn=978-0-8160-5368-1}}</ref> In addition, he was a proponent of the aviation industry; he was a sponsor of the [[Civil Aeronautics Act]] of 1938 and the Federal Airport Act of 1945, and was a proponent of establishing the [[United States Army Air Forces]] as the [[United States Air Force]] separate from the Army.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mccarran.com/NVAHOF/BiosTouchScreen/McCarran |title=Biography, HOF inductee Patrick A. McCarran |last=Nevada Aerospace Hall of Fame |website=Mccarran.com/NVAHOF/ |publisher=Clark County Department of Aviation |location=Las Vegas, NV |access-date=November 18, 2018}}</ref> He was also an ardent anti-Communist.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Carter |first1=Ralph G. |last2=Scott |first2= James M. |date=2009 |title=Choosing to Lead: Understanding Congressional Foreign Policy Entrepreneurs |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYzGTelSjcsC&pg=PA89 |location=Durham, NC |publisher=Duke University Press |page=89 |isbn=978-0-8223-4503-9 |author-link= }}</ref>\n\n[[Harold L. Ickes]] described McCarran as \"easy-going, old-shoe 'Pat'\" in a column criticizing McCarran as a tool of the oil companies, for not supporting certain regulations Ickes favored.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ickes |first=Harold |date=May 15, 1946 |title=Tidelands Should Not Worry Nevada Senator |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/104940193/ |work=[[The Indianapolis Star]] |location=Indianapolis, IN |page=12 |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> American journalist [[John Gunther]] was also critical of McCarran's alleged corporate ties, writing that he resembled gold \"in that he is soft, heavy, and not a good conductor.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Gunther|first=John|authorlink=John Gunther|title=Inside U.S.A.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/insideusa00guntrich/page/80 80], 84, 940|location=[[New York City|New York]]/[[London]]|publisher=[[Harper & Brothers]]|year=1947|title-link=Inside U.S.A. (book)}}</ref>\n\n[[File:U.S. Senator Pat McCarran handing mail bag to Pony Express rider, Dedication Ceremony, McCarran Air Field, Las Vegas, Nevada (74665).jpg|thumb|Postcard depicting McCarran at the dedication ceremony for the original McCarran Field, now [[Nellis Air Force Base]]]]\n[[McCarran International Airport]] located in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas, Nevada]] is named after Senator McCarran.<ref name=\"shaped\"/>  McCarran Boulevard in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] is named for Pat McCarran, as is McCarran Street in [[North Las Vegas, Nevada|North Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard N. |date=June 25, 2012 |title=Should McCarran airport be renamed for Las Vegas? |url=https://vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2012/jun/25/las-vegas-airport-needs-be-more-recognizable-outsi/ |newspaper=Vegas, Inc. |location=Las Vegas, NV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=John L. |date=August 28, 2012 |title=If we're erasing McCarran's name, maybe we should dump some others |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/john-l-smith/if-were-erasing-mccarrans-name-maybe-we-should-dump-some-others |newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal |location=Las Vegas, NV}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mccarran.jpg|thumb|left|[[Pat McCarran (Jacobson)|Statue]] in the National Statuary Hall Collection]]\nA [[Pat McCarran (Jacobson)|statue of McCarran]] is included in the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]] at the [[United States Capitol]].<ref name=\"shaped\"/>  Each state is allowed to display likenesses of two individuals; Nevada's are those of McCarran and [[Sarah Winnemucca]].<ref name=\"shaped\"/>\n\n===Possible statue removal===\nIn 2017, Nevada's three Democratic members of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] wrote to Governor [[Brian Sandoval]] and state legislative leaders and stated their view that review of McCarran's career might warrant removal of his statue from the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaley|first=Sean|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/nevada/nevada-lawmakers-favor-removing-mccarran-statue-us-capitol-poll|title=Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue from US Capitol|website=Reviewjournal.com|date=October 11, 2016|accessdate=January 12, 2017|ref={{sfnRef|\"Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue\"}}}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|While he fought for workers' rights and helped shape the country's aviation industry, McCarran left a legacy of racism, xenophobia and anti-Semitism, said the letter sent Tuesday by Reps. Dina Titus, Ruben Kihuen and Jacky Rosen.{{sfn|\"Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue\"}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Mel Lipman|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/sep/16/mccarrans-name-dishonors-nevada|title=McCarran's name dishonors Nevada - Las Vegas Sun News|website=Lasvegassun.com|accessdate=January 12, 2017|ref={{sfnRef|\"McCarran's name dishonors Nevada\"}}|date=September 16, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nOn January 11, 2017, it was reported that a poll of Nevada legislators indicated support for removing McCarran's statue from the collection.{{sfn|\"Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue\"}}  A bill introduced in the [[Nevada State Senate]], SB 174, which called for the removal of the statue and renaming of [[McCarran International Airport]] for former U.S. Senator [[Harry Reid]], failed to be passed before the end of the 2017 legislative session on June 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaley |first=Sean |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/2017-legislature/las-vegas-airport-will-not-get-a-name-change/ |title=Las Vegas airport will not get a name change \u2013 Las Vegas Review-Journal |publisher=Reviewjournal.com |date=June 6, 2017 |accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\n*Cartoonist [[Walt Kelly]] introduced a character into his ''[[Pogo (comic strip)|Pogo]]'' comic strip called Mole MacCaroney. Mole's near-blindness and concerns about \"germs\" were seen as a reference to McCarran and his immigration restriction policies.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dave in Northridge |date=November 28, 2012 |title=Top Comments: Okefenokee Swamp Edition |url= |newspaper=Daily Kos}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Black |first=James Eric |date=2016 |title=Walt Kelly and Pogo: The Art of the Political Swamp |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=umlECwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199 |location=Jefferson, NC |publisher=McFarland & Company |page=199 |isbn=978-0-7864-7987-0}}</ref>\n*McCarran was in part the inspiration for the fictional character of the corrupt United States Senator [[Pat Geary]] in the film ''[[The Godfather Part II]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=G.D. Spradlin, 1920-2011|url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-07-26/ae/29817237_1_spradlin-single-movie-geary|accessdate=December 23, 2011|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=July 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hoffman |first=Dave |date=March 6, 2007 |title=The Godfather's Connection to the US Attorney Scandal |url=https://concurringopinions.com/archives/2007/03/a_blast_from_th.html |newspaper=Concurring Opinions}}</ref>\n*McCarran's chair from his tenure in the U.S. Senate was featured on an episode of the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] reality television series ''[[Pawn Stars]]''.<ref>[[List of Pawn Stars episodes#Season 3|A listing of Season 3 episodes with synopses of the '''History''' channel reality TV series ''Pawn Stars'']]</ref>\n*In the video game, ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]'', the post-apocalyptic remains of [[McCarran International Airport]] have been turned into a New California Republic military base named Camp McCarran.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.falloutnewvegastour.com/2011/04/location-18-camp-mccarran.html |title=Fallout New Vegas Tour: Location 18; Camp McCarran |last=Worth |first=Chris |date=April 14, 2011 |website=Fallout: New Vegas Tour |publisher=Chris Worth}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1950\u201399)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Klingaman\n  | first = William\n  | title = The Encyclopedia of the McCarthy Era\n  | publisher = New York : Facts on File\n  | year = 1996\n  | isbn = 0-8160-3097-9\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofmc0000klin\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Ybarra\n  | first = Michael J.\n  | title = Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt\n  | publisher = Steerforth Publishing\n  | year = 2004\n  | isbn = 1-58642-065-8\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/washingtongonecr0000ybar\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Newman\n  | first = Robert P.\n  | title = Owen Lattimore And The \"Loss\" of China\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/owenlattimorelos0000newm\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = Berkeley : University of California Press\n  | year = 1992\n  | isbn = 0-520-07388-6}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last =Schrecker\n  | first =Ellen\n  | title =No Ivory Tower : McCarthyism and the Universities\n  | publisher =New York : Oxford University Press\n  | year =1986\n  | isbn =0-19-503557-7\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/noivorytowermcca00schr\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last =Schrecker\n  | first =Ellen\n  | title =Many Are The Crimes : McCarthyism In America\n  | publisher =Boston; London : Little, Brown\n  | year =1998\n  | isbn =0-316-77470-7\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/manyarecrimesmcc00schr\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  | last =Hopkins\n  | first = A. D.\n  | title = Pat McCarran, Perennial Politician\n  | work = The First 100; Portraits of the Men and Women Who Shaped Las Vegas\n  | publisher = Stephens Media Group\n  | year = 1999\n  | url = http://www.1st100.com/part2/mccarran.html\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  | title = \tPatrick McCarran (1876&ndash;1954)\n  | work = Las Vegas: An Unconventional History\n  | publisher = American Experience, PBS\n  | year = 2005\n  | url = https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/lasvegas/peopleevents/p_mccarran.html\n }}\n\n===By Pat McCarran===\n*{{cite book\n  | last = McCarran\n  | first = Pat\n  | title = Three years of the Federal Administrative Procedure Act: A study in Legislation\n  | publisher = Georgetown Law Journal Association\n  | year =1950\n  | id =  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = McCarran\n  | first = Pat\n  | title = Build the West to Build the Nation; Address Before Guests And Members of the Board of Trustees of Builders of the West, Inc.\n }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = McCarran\n  | first = Pat\n  | title = Displaced Persons: Facts Versus Fiction\n  | publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office\n  }}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|M000308}}\n*{{Findagrave|7125891}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Pat McCarran}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box|\n before=[[Tasker Oddie]]|\n state=Nevada|class=3|\n after=[[Ernest S. Brown]]|\n years=1933\u20131954\n|alongside=[[Key Pittman]], [[Berkeley L. Bunker]],<br>[[James G. Scrugham]], [[Edward P. Carville]], [[George W. Malone]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Columbia|Senate District of Columbia Committee]]\n|before=[[William H. King]]<br>Utah\n|after=[[Theodore G. Bilbo]]<br>Mississippi\n|years=1941\u20131945}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]]\n|before=[[Frederick Van Nuys]]<br>Indiana\n|after=[[Alexander Wiley]]<br>Wisconsin\n|years=1945\u20131947}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]]\n|before=[[Alexander Wiley]]<br>Wisconsin\n|after=[[William Langer]]<br>North Dakota\n|years=1949\u20131953}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USSenNV}}\n{{SenJudiciaryCommitteeChairs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCarran, Pat}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Nevada]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:District attorneys in Nevada]]\n[[Category:McCarthyism]]\n[[Category:Members of the Nevada Assembly]]\n[[Category:Nevada Democrats]]\n[[Category:Nevada Supreme Court justices]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Reno, Nevada]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Nevada]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Reno alumni]]\n[[Category:Reno High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Anti-immigration politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Nevada Supreme Court]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Pat McCarran\n| image name = Nevada Senator. Washington, D.C., April 24. A new informal picture of Senator Pat McCarran, democrat of Nevada LCCN2016875505 (cropped).jpg\n| jr/sr1 = United States Senator\n| state1 = [[Nevada]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| term_start1 = March 4, 1933\n| term_end1 = September 28, 1954\n| preceded1 = [[Tasker Oddie]]\n| succeeded1 = [[Ernest S. Brown]]\n| office2 = Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]]\n| term2 = January 2, 1917 \u2013 January 4, 1919\n| preceded2 = [[Frank Herbert Norcross]]\n| succeeded2 =[[Benjamin Wilson Coleman]]\n| office3 = Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]]\n| term3 = January 2, 1913 \u2013 January 1, 1917\n| preceded3 = [[James G. Sweeney]]\n| succeeded3 =[[Edward Augustus Ducker]]\n| office4 = [[District Attorney]] of [[Nye County, Nevada]]\n| term_start4 = 1907\n| term_end4 = 1909\n| predecessor4 = W. B Pittman\n| successor4 = Cleve H. Baker\n| office5 = Member of the [[Nevada Assembly]] from [[Washoe County, Nevada|Washoe County]]\n| term_start5 = 1903\n| term_end5 = 1905\n| alongside5 = Peter Burke; W. D. R. Graham, H. R. Cooke, A. D. Graham, J. F. Crosby, J. E. Soucherau\n| predecessor5 = Phil Jacobs, G. E. Peckham, W. W. Webster\n| successor5 = Walter Hastings, A. W. Holmes, E. R. Dodge, R. H. Kinney, J. W. Wright, J. S. Orr\n| birth_name = Patrick Anthony McCarran\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1876|8|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Reno, Nevada]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1954|9|28|1876|8|8}}\n| death_place = [[Hawthorne, Nevada]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Mountain View Cemetery, Reno, Nevada\n| profession= Lawyer\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Anthony McCarran''' (August 8, 1876 \u2013 September 28, 1954) was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from [[History of Nevada|Nevada]] from 1933 until 1954.  McCarran was born in [[Reno, Nevada]], attended [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada State University]], and was a farmer and rancher.  In 1902 he won election to the [[Nevada Assembly]], but in 1904 he was an unsuccessful candidate for the [[Nevada State Senate]].  He completed private law studies and was admitted to the bar in 1905; in 1906 he won election as [[Nye County, Nevada|Nye County]]'s [[district attorney]]. He served a two-year term, after which he relocated to Reno.\n\nFrom 1913 to 1917, McCarran was an associate justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]], and he served as chief justice from 1917 to 1919.  In 1932 McCarran defeated Republican incumbent [[Tasker Oddie]] for [[List of United States Senators from Nevada|Nevada's Class 3 Senate seat]] to become the state's first U.S. Senator born in Nevada; he was reelected three times, and served from 1933 until his death. In his Senate career, McCarran served as chairman of the District of Columbia, Judiciary, and Joint Foreign Economic Cooperation Committees. He died in [[Hawthorne, Nevada]] and was buried at Mountain View Cemetery in Reno. [[McCarran International Airport]] in [[Las Vegas]] was later named in his honor.\n\nMcCarran is remembered as one of the few Democrats to reject the [[New Deal]]. In addition, he was a proponent of the aviation industry; he was a sponsor of the [[Civil Aeronautics Act]] of 1938, and was a proponent of establishing the [[United States Air Force]] as a separate entity from the [[United States Army|Army]]. McCarran was also an ardent anti-Communist, to the point of supporting fascists including [[Francisco Franco]] as a way to prevent its spread, and sponsored the [[McCarran Act]], otherwise known as the [[Subversive Activities Control Act of 1950]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMcCarran was born in [[Reno, Nevada]], the child of [[Irish American|Irish immigrants]] Margaret Shay and Patrick McCarran.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Browne|first1=Blaine Terry|last2=Cottrell |first2=Robert C.|date=2010|title=Lives and Times - Individuals and Issues in American History Since 1865|url=https://archive.org/details/livestimesindivi0000brow|url-access=registration|location=Lanham, MD|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|page=[https://archive.org/details/livestimesindivi0000brow/page/173 173]|isbn=978-0-7425-6193-9}}</ref>  He was educated in Reno and in 1897, he graduated as [[valedictorian]] of his class at [[Reno High School]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\">{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Jerome E.|date=1982|title=Pat McCarran, Political Boss of Nevada|url=https://archive.org/details/patmccarranpolit0000edwa|url-access=registration|location=Reno, NV|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-071-9}}</ref>{{rp|[https://archive.org/details/patmccarranpolit0000edwa/page/3 3]\u20134, 7}} McCarran's mother was a devout Catholic, and he inherited his mother's faith.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|1-2}}\n\nHe attended the [[University of Nevada, Reno]], but withdrew to work on the family sheep ranch when his father suffered an injury.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> He [[reading law|studied law]] with [[William Woodburn]], and served in the [[Nevada Assembly]] from 1903 to 1905.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> In 1904 he was an unsuccessful candidate for the [[Nevada State Senate]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1905, and in 1906 he was elected [[district attorney]] of [[Nye County, Nevada|Nye County]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/> He served one term, 1907 to 1909, after which he moved to Reno to continue practicing law.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>\n\nSome sources incorrectly state that McCarran received a bachelor's degree in 1901 and a master's degree in 1915.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rocha|first=Guy|date=May 2001|title= Myth #64: Getting the Facts Down Pat|url=http://nsla.nv.gov/Archives/Myths/Getting_the_Facts_Down_Pat/ |location=Carson City|publisher=Nevada State Library and Archives|page=1}}</ref> In fact, he did not receive a bachelor's degree at all, and the [[master of arts]] he received from [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada State University]] in 1915 was an [[honorary degree]].<ref>{{cite book|last=University of Nevada|date=November 1, 1922|title=Quarterly Bulletin|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3xXOAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA37&dq=mccarran+%22university+of+nevada%22+%22M.A.%22+1915#v=onepage&q=mccarran%20%22university%20of%20nevada%22%20%22M.A.%22%201915&f=false|location=Reno, NV|publisher=University of Nevada|page=33}}</ref> He also received an honorary [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from [[Georgetown University]] in 1943,<ref>{{cite news|title=Georgetown U. to Confer Degree on Senator M'Carran|work= The Guardian (Little Rock)|page=5|date=September 10, 1943|url=http://arc.stparchive.com/Archive/ARC/ARC09101943p05.php}}</ref> and an honorary [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from the University of Nevada in 1945.<ref>{{cite book|last=University of Nevada Board of Regents|date=1946|title=Biennial Report of the Board of Regents of the State University of Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/?id=y2RMAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22mccarran%22+%22nevada%22+%22ll.d.%22+1945&q=mccarran|location=Reno|publisher=University of Nevada|page=21}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career==\nIn 1912, McCarran was elected to the [[Supreme Court of Nevada]], succeeding John G. Sweeney.<ref>{{cite book|last=Davis |first=Sam Post|date=1913|title=The History of Nevada|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ebcUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA306|location=Reno, NV|publisher=Elms Publishing Co.|page=306}}</ref> He served as an Associate Justice from January 1913 to January 1917.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\">{{cite news|date=January 2, 1917|title=M'Carran Is New Chief Justice|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/147917797|newspaper=Reno Gazette-Journal|location=Reno, NV|page=3|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn January 1917, he succeeded [[Frank Herbert Norcross]] as Chief Justice.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 12, 1917 |title=Judge McCarran Chosen Chief Justice of Court |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/375520722/ |work=The Pioche Record |location=Pioche, NV |page=1 |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1918,<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/> and served until January 1919, when he was succeeded on the court by Edward Augustus Ducker, and as Chief Justice by Benjamin Wilson Coleman.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/>\n\nBoth during his time on the court and afterwards, McCarran continued to play a central role in Nevada's state government, as well as its legal and criminal justice systems. From 1913 to 1918, he served on the state Board of Library Commissioners.<ref>{{cite book|date=1955|title=United States Code Congressional and Administrative News|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Kus0AQAAIAAJ&dq=%22mccarran%22+%22nevada%22+%22library+commission%22+1913+1918&q=%22library+commission%22|publisher=West Publishing Company|location=Eagan, Minnesota|page=42}}</ref> In addition, he served as chairman of the [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada State University]] Board of Visitors.<ref>{{cite book|last=Farnsworth|first=Joe|date=1917|title=List of Members, Officers and Committees and Rules of the Two Houses of the Nevada Legislature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0h8uAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA8|location=Carson City, NV|publisher=State Printing Company|page=8}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1913 to 1919 he served on the state Board of Pardons.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia of Nevada\">{{cite book|date=2000|title=Encyclopedia of Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oLd4nCEMbpUC&pg=PA194|location=Santa Barbara, CA|publisher=Somerset Publishers, Inc.|page=194|isbn=978-0-403-09611-4|ref={{sfnRef|''Encyclopedia of Nevada''}}}}</ref> He was a member of the Board of Parole Commissioners from 1913 to 1918, and he served on the Board of Bar Examiners from 1919 until 1932.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia of Nevada\"/>\n\nMcCarran was president of the Nevada Bar Association from 1920 to 1921, and was a vice president of the [[American Bar Association]] from 1922 to 1923.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCarran|first=Pat|date=May 1, 1939|title=My Views on Senate Bill 1635|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cz9AxBg8l_wC&pg=RA1-PA36|journal=Popular Aviation|location=Chicago, Illinois|publisher=Ziff-Davis Publishing Company|page=36}}</ref>\n\n==United States Senate==\n===Election history===\nMcCarran's ambition to serve as a U.S. Senator was well known in Nevada, and often the subject of jokes in the press. He ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic nomination in 1916, and lost to incumbent [[Key Pittman]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rothman|first=Hal|date=2010|title=The Making of Modern Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YzgOWKpnBGcC&pg=PA79|location=Reno, NV|publisher=University of Nevada Press|page=79|isbn=978-0-87417-826-5}}</ref> McCarran endorsed Pittman in the general election, and Pittman was reelected.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/>\n\nIn 1926, McCarran was again a candidate for the U.S. Senate. He lost the Democratic nomination to [[Raymond T. Baker]], who was defeated by Republican incumbent [[Tasker Oddie]] in the general election.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/>\n\nIn 1932, McCarran was the Democratic nominee, and he defeated Oddie in the general election.<ref name=\"renogazjournal\"/> He was reelected in [[United States Senate elections, 1938|1938]], [[United States Senate elections, 1944|1944]], and [[United States Senate elections, 1950|1950]], and served from March 4, 1933 until his death.<ref name=Late_a_Senator>{{cite book|date=1955|title=Patrick Anthony McCarran, Late a Senator from Nevada|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015002677295;view=1up;seq=11|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=US Government Printing Office|page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Leadership positions===\nDuring his career as a Senator, McCarran served as chairman of the: [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Columbia|Committee on the District of Columbia]] ([[77th United States Congress|77th]] and [[78th United States Congress|78th]] Congresses); [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]] ([[78th United States Congress|78th]], [[79th United States Congress|79th]], [[81st United States Congress|81st]], and [[82nd United States Congress|82nd]] Congresses); and [[List of defunct United States congressional committees#Defunct Joint Committees|Joint Committee on Foreign Economic Cooperation]] ([[81st United States Congress]]) (co-chairman).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000308|title=Patrick Anthony McCarran profile|last=Historian of the United States Senate|website=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|publisher=United States Senate|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition to Roosevelt administration===\nDuring his first term as senator, McCarran was engaged in a major struggle for the control of patronage appointments relating to federal projects in Nevada with his fellow Democratic Senator, [[Key Pittman]].<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69}} As Nevada was a poor state badly hit by the Great Depression, there was considerable competition to be awarded a patronage appointment, and those who had control of patronage were in a strong position politically. As Pittman was the senior senator, and McCarran only a freshman senator, President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] tended to side with Pittman in the struggle for the control of patronage, thus earning McCarran's enmity.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70}} Much of McCarran's opposition to the New Deal stemmed from his anger and spite that Pittman was able to make more patronage appointments relating to New Deal projects in Nevada than he was.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70}} Pittman's increasing serious drinking problems rendered him somewhat ineffective in his last years, and McCarran was able to gradually take over the Democratic Party in Nevada, becoming the dominant force within the Nevada Democrats by 1938.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70, 74}}\n\nDespite being a Democrat, beginning in the late 1930s McCarran came into increasing opposition with Roosevelt, believing that Roosevelt's \"second\" New Deal policies following his 1936 reelection were too liberal.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} Further complicating the picture was that by 1939, Roosevelt was convinced that the Danzig crisis would probably lead to a war in Europe, and that it was in the best interests of the United States to ensure that Britain and France defeated Germany, which would require relaxing the various Neutrality Acts passed by Congress earlier in the 1930s. As Pittman was chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, his co-operation was essential. Thus for foreign policy reasons, Roosevelt had to back Pittman despite the way he was losing control of the Nevada Democrats to McCarran.  From 1939 to 1941, the isolationist McCarran opposed Roosevelt's foreign policy of aiding the Allies, accusing the president of trying to involve America in a war that not its business.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} In particular, the Catholic conservative McCarran was outraged by the decision of the Roosevelt administration to offer military and economic aid to the Soviet Union in the summer of 1941, arguing that it was immoral to assist the \"godless communists\".<ref name=\"auto3\">Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 271</ref> In a speech on the Senate floor, McCarran declared that \"I despise Mr. Hitler and all that he stands for, and equally I despise Mr. Stalin and all that he stands for\", before going on to argue that through he did not like Nazi Germany that he regarded the Third Reich as the lesser evil compared to the Soviet Union, and felt it was profoundly wrong for the United States to offer aid to the nation he felt was the greater evil.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> McCarran was greatly influenced by a statement from the Catholic Church in the summer of 1941 declaring that \"Communism is intrinsically wrong, and no one who would save Christian civilization may collaborate with it in any undertaking\".<ref name=\"auto3\"/> McCarran supported the war effort after the United States entered the conflict following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor.\n\nMcCarran's positions on several key committees, most notably Appropriations and Judiciary, gave him significant influence that he used to obtain federal funding for Nevada, a fact which contributed substantially to his home state popularity.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|122-123}} In 1944, McCarran was challenged by [[Vail M. Pittman]] in the Democratic primary, leading to an especially hard-fought campaign that was finally won by McCarran.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|119}} At the time, Pittman explained his loss as due to McCarran's ability to bring federal money to fund infrastructure projects in Nevada, at the time a relatively backward state, saying: <blockquote>\"McCarran had a pet project in nearly every town in the state. Housing projects, sewage systems, airfields, power projects, school houses and heaven knows what...People remember the little personal favors and the things that help financially, but they forgot all the things done that are more remote, but more vital\".<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|119}}</blockquote> McCarran's biographer, Jerome Edwards, endorsed this theory, arguing that the narrow margin of McCarran's victory over Pittman in the Democratic primary suggests that a substantial number of registered Democrats in Nevada were dissatisfied with him, but his ability to have the federal government built infrastructure projects that Nevada could not afford on its own explains his enduring appeal in his state.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|119}} Outside of Nevada, McCarran had the reputation of a narrow-minded and parochial  senator who put the interests of Nevada ahead of the wider national interests; the same reasons that made him unpopular outside of Nevada made him popular there as he had the reputation of a dogged, relentless fighter for Nevada's interests.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} McCarran's repeatedly attempted via filibusters to force the federal government to stockpile silver, a measure that would have benefited Nevada where silver mining was a major industry, but was widely denounced outside of Nevada as a plan for wasteful spending designed only to benefit his state.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}} After Pearl Harbor, McCarran in his speeches to the Senate made much of the fact that most of American industry was concentrated in the Northeast and the Midwest, and argued that the federal government had the duty to ensure that war production was shifted to less industrialized states like Nevada.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94-95}}\n\nMcCarran also was well known for his efforts to help constituents with any problems that they might have with the federal government, often going to extraordinary lengths.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|122-124}} For instance, when a teenager from Nevada stolen 150 volumes from the [[Library of Congress]] and mutilated hundreds of more books, his parents asked McCarran to intervene to ensure that their son was not prosecuted.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|123}} McCarran duly called up the Washington D.C. District Attorney  [[Edward Curran]] and the FBI director, [[J. Edgar Hoover]], saying he not want the teenager prosecuted as that would cost him the votes of the parents of the bibliophobic vandal-thief, and owing to the senator's advocacy, the teenager was not prosecuted despite the overwhelming evidence of his guilt and his theft and destruction of books costing thousands of dollars.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|1234}} in 1942, when a Reno couple learned that their son had been captured by the Japanese at Wake Island, they appealed to McCarran for help.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|123}} McCarran brought considerable pressure to bear on the State Department to set up a prisoner exchange, saying that it essential for him to keep the two votes of the parents of the POW, through the State Department insisted that the United States was not in the business of prisoner exchanges, which would involve making deals with the Axis powers that the American people would find unsavory.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|124-125}}\n\nIn the 1940s-50s, 40% of Senate bills had to first be approved by the Senate Judiciary committee, giving McCarran immense power as he could easily \"kill\" these bills in his committee<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|94}}<ref name=\"auto1\">Oshinksy, David ''A Conspiracy So Immense'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005 page 207.</ref> Other committee chairmen had the same powers over bills related to their fields, but the number of bills that had to passed by the Judiciary Committee made McCarran far more influential than the other senate committee chairmen.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Over time, McCarran used his position as chairman of the Judiciary Committee to engage in much deal-making that allowed him to collect a significant number of political \"debts\", making him of the most powerful Senators.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|69-70}} McCarran's conservative politics, which pitted him against first Roosevelt and then Truman, frequently led to the question being asked why he continue to sit as a Democrat instead of defecting over to the Republicans. In 1950, when McCarran asked that question by a reporter, he responded: \"I can do more good by staying in the Democratic Party and watching the lunatic fringe-the Roosevelt crowd\".<ref name=\"auto\">Oshinksy, David ''A Conspiracy So Immense'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005 page 208.</ref> McCarran was against the plans of the Roosevelt-Truman administrations for federal health insurance and increased education spending; favored restricting the power of unions; was opposed to increased immigration, saying he did not want \"undesirables from abroad\" coming to America; and was against the United Nations, which he called \"a haven for spies and Communists\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> As chairman of the Judiciary Committee, he appointed his friend, Senator [[James Eastland]], a well known white supremacist and segregationist, as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Civil Rights.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Such was McCarran's power that in July 1952, the liberal ''Washington Post'' newspaper (which was not friendly to the conservative McCarran) declared in an article: \"It sums the character of this congress to state an unquestionable fact: that its most important member was Patrick A. McCarran\".<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|122-147}}\n\n===Aviation advocate===\nMcCarran sponsored numerous laws concerning the early commercial aviation industry, including the [[Civil Aeronautics Act]] of 1938 and the Federal Airport Act of 1945.<ref name=\"Late_a_Senator\"/> He was an early advocate of the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] as a military component separate from the Army, and began sponsoring the necessary legislation in 1933.<ref name=\"shaped\">[http://www.1st100.com/part2/mccarran.html The First 100 Persons Who Shaped Southern Nevada], 1st100.com; accessed December 12, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Other initiatives===\nIn 1945, McCarran co-sponsored the [[McCarran-Ferguson Act]], which exempted the insurance industry from most federal regulations, including [[Antitrust law|antitrust]] rules.  Instead, this act required states to regulate insurance, including mandatory licensing requirements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statefarm.com/about-us/company-overview/company-profile/insurance-industry-issues/the-mccarran-ferguson-act|title=What is the McCarran-Ferguson Act?|website=Company Overview: McCarran-Ferguson Act|publisher=State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company|location=Bloomington, IL|access-date=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMcCarran also co-sponsored the 1946 [[Administrative Procedure Act (United States)|Administrative Procedures Act]], which required federal agencies to keep the public informed of their organizational structure, procedures and rules, allowed for public participation in the rule making process, and established uniform standards for the conduct of formal rule making.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grisinger|first=Joanna L.|date=2012|title=The Unwieldy American State: Administrative Politics since the New Deal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GU0gAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA77|location=New York, NY|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=77|isbn=978-1-107-00432-0}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-communist===\n[[File:Pat McCarran (Nevada) (1947).jpg|thumb|[[Harris & Ewing photo studio|Harris & Ewing]] portrait of McCarran in 1947]]\nMcCarran established himself as one of the Senate's most ardent anti-Communists.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ceplair|first=Larry|date=2011|title=Anti-communism in Twentieth-century America: A Critical History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pNAKcnXoMCgC&pg=PA97|location=Santa Barbara, CA|publisher=ABC CLIO|page=97|isbn=978-1-4408-0047-4}}</ref> An admirer of Spanish dictator [[Francisco Franco]], he was nicknamed the \"Senator from Madrid\" by columnist [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]] over his efforts to increase [[foreign aid]] to Spain.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carter|first1=Ralph G.|last2=Scott|first2=James M.|date=2009|title=Choosing to Lead: Understanding Congressional Foreign Policy Entrepreneurs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYzGTelSjcsC&pg=PA89|location=Durham, NC|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=89\u201390|isbn=978-0-8223-4503-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ybarra|first=Michael J.|date=2004|title=Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mVl3AAAAMAAJ&dq=mccarran+pearson+%22senator+from+madrid%22&q=%22senator+from+madrid%22|location=Hanover, NH|publisher=Steerforth Press|page=504|isbn=978-1-58642-065-9}}</ref> McCarran voted for President [[Harry S. Truman]]'s 1947 plan to provide aid to Greece and Turkey as part of an effort to prevent them from becoming communist, but in 1949 McCarran broke with Truman after he rejected McCarran's request for increased economic aid to Spain and military aid to [[Chiang Kai-shek]]'s nationalist Chinese government.<ref name=\"polbossofNevada\"/>{{rp|132}} In 1949, McCarran visited Spain, where he was treated like a visiting head of state, and he made it clear his admiration for ''El Caudillo'' (\"the leader\") as Franco had styled himself in imitation of Mussolini and Hitler.<ref>Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 pages 473-474</ref> McCarran's praise for Franco, who had leaned in a pro-Axis neutrality for much of World War II, greatly annoyed Truman who told the press that: \"I don't like Franco and I never will\".<ref>Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 474</ref> During his visit to Spain, McCarran met with Franco to discuss U.S aid for his regime, which infuriated Truman who noted that the constitution gave the executive the right to conduct foreign policy, which led him to angrily declare that the senator from Nevada did not have the right to conduct his own foreign policy.<ref>Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 475</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], McCarran continued his anti-Communist efforts. He was a supporter of [[Chiang Kai-shek]], whose \"[[loss of China]]\" to communists in 1949 he blamed on Soviet influence in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Leffler|first=Melvyn P.|date=1992|title=A Preponderance of Power: National Security, the Truman Administration, and the Cold War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pIIeG_yn72wC&pg=PA295|location=Stanford, CA|publisher=Stanford University Press|page=295|isbn=9780804722186}}</ref> In 1952, McCarran attended a dinner hosted by the [[Kuomintang]] Chinese Ambassador to Washington together with Republican Senators [[Joseph McCarthy]] and [[William Knowland]]; the event began with the toast \"Back to the mainland!\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gillon|first1=Steven M.|last2=Kunz|first2=Diane B.|date=1993|title=America During the Cold War|url=https://books.google.com/?id=e4QaAQAAIAAJ&dq=mccarran+%22back+to+the+mainland%22&q=%22back+to+the+mainland%22|location=San Diego, CA|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|page=58|isbn=9780155004153}}</ref> McCarthy sought McCarran's favor after he started his \"crusade against Communism\", giving \"hot tips\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> McCarran told his friends that \"Joe is a bit irresponsible\" and a \"publicity hound\", but praised him for his attacks on the Truman administration.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 1951, in an interview with the ''U.S. News'', McCarran replied to the questions asked that he believed that the American Communist Party had been engaging in the \"infiltration\" of the media, churches, university faculties, unions and \"nationality groups\".<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn August\u2013September 1950, McCarran was the chief sponsor of the [[McCarran Internal Security Act]]. This legislation required the [[Communist Party USA]] and affiliated organizations to register with the [[Attorney General of the United States|Attorney General]] and established the [[Subversive Activities Control Board]] to investigate possible communist subversion and communist front organizations. The act also gave the government the power to imprison without trial of people \"likely\" to be spies, saboteurs, and \"subversives\" if the president declared a national emergency, through those imprisoned could appeal to a review board.<ref name=\"auto4\">Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 117.</ref> President [[Harry S. Truman]] vetoed the act, charging that it violated civil liberties and put the government in \"the business of thought control\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/> In the \"hot summer\" of 1950, with the [[Korean War]] raging abroad and the [[Red Scare#Second Red Scare (1947\u201360)|Second Red Scare]] at home, few in Congress wanted to be appear \"soft\" on communism, and Congress overrode Truman's veto, with the House voting 248 to 48 and the Senate 57 to 10, forcing Truman to reluctantly enforce a law he felt violated the Bill of Rights.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> After passage of the act, the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] built six concentration camps (either old POW camps from World War II or abandoned military bases) to hold \"subversives\" if a national emergency was declared.<ref name=\"auto6\">Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 118.</ref> No such emergency was ever declared and the camps were never used before being shut down in 1957 as a cost-cutting measure.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Due to numerous hearings, delays and [[appeal]]s, the act was never enforced, and its major provisions were declared unconstitutional by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in 1965 and 1967.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fried|first=Richard M.|year=1990|title=Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=187|isbn=0-19-504361-8}}</ref>\n\nAs chairman of the Judiciary Committee, McCarran created and was the first chairman of the [[Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]] that investigated the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[Harry S. Truman]] administrations to expose supposed communist spies and sympathizers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Black|first=James Eric|date=2016|title=Walt Kelly and Pogo: The Art of the Political Swamp|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=umlECwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|location=Jefferson, NC|publisher=McFarland & Company|page=199|isbn=978-0-7864-7987-0}}</ref> In 1951, subcommittee investigators seized the records of the [[Institute of Pacific Relations]] in an effort to identify alleged communist infiltration of the organization, which had been formed in 1925 to foster cooperation between Pacific Rim nations.<ref>{{cite book|last=Newman|first=Robert P.|title=Owen Lattimore and the \"loss\" of China|url=https://archive.org/details/owenlattimorelos0000newm|url-access=registration|location=Berkeley, CA|publisher=University of California Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/owenlattimorelos0000newm/page/318 318]|isbn=978-0-520-07388-3|date=March 2, 1992}}</ref>  McCarran made much of these records when questioning a [[Sinologist]], [[Owen Lattimore]], in acrimonious hearings over 12 days in February 1951.<ref name=\"auto11\">Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 148</ref> In March 1950, Senator McCarthy accused Lattimore of being the \"top Russian agent\" responsible for the \"loss of China\", thereby making Lattimore, a previously little known expert on China, into an internationally famous figure. During the hearings, it became quickly apparent that McCarran and Lattimore deeply disliked each other with the two men frequently engaging in shouting matches and interrupting one another.<ref name=\"auto12\">Oshinksy, David ''A Conspiracy So Immense'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005 page 209.</ref> When it was established that Lattimore had met President Truman in 1945 to discuss America's China policy, McCarran sarcastically commented: \"He visited the President once and forgot it\".<ref name=\"auto11\"/> McCarran demanded that Lattimore prove a negative, asking him \"can you say that the IPR and you had no influence on upon the Far Eastern experts in the State Department?\"<ref name=\"auto11\"/> McCarran worked to establish that Lattimore was the man responsible for the \"loss of China\", claiming General [[George Marshall]]'s policy during his 1945 to 1947 diplomatic mission to China during that country's civil war between nationalists and communists as being \"substantially the same\" as that recommended by Lattimore.<ref name=\"auto11\"/> At the end of the hearings, McCarran gave Lattimore what was described as a \"tongue lashing\", stating he was \"so flagrantly defiant\" and \"so persistent in his efforts to confuse and obscure the facts that the committee feels constrained to take due notice of his conduct...That he has uttered untruths stands clear in the record\".<ref name=\"auto11\"/> The report of the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee written by McCarran concluded that China was indeed \"lost\" because of the policy followed by the State Department, declaring: \"Owen Lattimore and John Carter Vincent were influential in bringing about a change in United States policy...favorable to the Chinese Communists\".<ref name=\"auto12\"/> Through McCarran was careful not to call Lattimore a Soviet spy in his report, which would have allowed him to sue for libel, he came very close with the statement: \"Owen Lattimore was, from some time beginning in the 1930s, a conscious, articulate instrument of the Soviet conspiracy\".<ref name=\"auto12\"/>\n\nMcCarran subsequently pushed successfully for Lattimore to be [[indictment|indicted]] for [[perjury]]. As chairman of the Judiciary Committee, he held up the nomination of Truman's nominee for Attorney General, [[James McGranery]], until McGanery promised to indict Lattimore.<ref>Fried, Richard ''Nightmare in Red: The McCarthy Era in Perspective'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990 page 149.</ref> Lattimore's lawyer [[Abe Fortas]] defended him by claiming McCarran had deliberately asked questions about arcane and obscure matters that took place in the 1930s in the hope that Lattimore would not be able to recall them properly, thereby giving grounds for perjury indictments. Federal Judge [[Luther Youngdahl]] later dismissed all seven charges against Lattimore on the grounds that the matters in question were insubstantial, of little concern to McCarran's inquiry, or the result of questions phrased in such a way that they could not be fairly answered.<ref>Haynes & Klehr ''Early Cold War Spies''; p. 47; US Senate, 82nd Congress, 2nd Session, Committee on the Judiciary, Institute of Pacific Relations, Report No. 2050, p. 224</ref>\n\nOn 27 July 1953, the [[Korean Armistice Agreement|armistice of Panmunjom]] was signed ending the Korean War. McCarran attracted national attention when he criticized President Dwight Eisenhower on the Senate floor for signing the armistice, which he called \"a perpetuation of a fraud on this country and the United Nations\".<ref name=\"auto7\">Ybarra, Michael J. ''Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt'', Hanover: Steerforth Press, 2004 page 714</ref> McCarran believed that the United States and the rest of its allies fighting under the united Nations banner in Korea should have fought on until all of Korea was unified under the leadership of President [[Syngman Rhee]], which led him to see the armistice as a sort of American defeat.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\n===Changes to immigration law===\nIn June 1952, McCarran joined [[Francis Walter]] in sponsorship of the [[McCarran&ndash;Walter Act]], a law that abolished racial restrictions found in United States immigration and naturalization statutes going back to the Naturalization Act of 1790 and also imposed more rigid restrictions on quotas for immigrants entering the United States. It also stiffened the existing law relating to the admission, exclusion and deportation of dangerous aliens (as defined by the McCarran Internal Security Act). In response to the act he made a well known statement:\n\n{{quote|I believe that this nation is the last hope of Western civilization and if this oasis of the world shall be overrun, perverted, contaminated or destroyed, then the last flickering light of humanity will be extinguished. I take no issue with those who would praise the contributions which have been made to our society by people of many races, of varied creeds and colors. America is indeed a joining together of many streams which go to form a mighty river which we call the American way. However, we have in the United States today hard-core, indigestible blocs which have not become integrated into the American way of life, but which, on the contrary are its deadly enemies. Today, as never before, untold millions are storming our gates for admission and those gates are cracking under the strain. The solution of the problems of Europe and Asia will not come through a transplanting of those problems en masse to the United States.... I do not intend to become prophetic, but if the enemies of this legislation succeed in riddling it to pieces, or in amending it beyond recognition, they will have contributed more to promote this nation's downfall than any other group since we achieved our independence as a nation.<ref>Senator Pat McCarran, Congressional Record, March 2, 1953, p. 1518</ref>}}\n\nSome of the immigration provisions of the act were later superseded by the [[1965 Immigration Act]], but the power of the government to deny visas for ideological reasons remained on the books another 25 years after that.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holmes |first=Steven A. |date=February 2, 1990 |title=Legislation Eases Limits on Aliens |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/02/us/legislation-eases-limits-on-aliens.html |work=New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\n==Death and burial==\nMcCarran died in [[Hawthorne, Nevada]] on September 28, 1954, shortly after leaving the stage following a speech he gave at a political rally.<ref name=\"Late_a_Senator\"/><ref name=Dies>{{cite news |last=Sun Staff |date=September 29, 1954 |title=McCarran Dies: Senator Collapses After Speaking to Hawthorne Demo |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1954/sep/29/mccarran-dies/ |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |location=Las Vegas, NV}}</ref>  According to news accounts published after his death, McCarran suffered a fatal heart attack, after having recovered from attacks in 1951 and 1953.<ref name=\"Dies\"/> McCarran was buried at Mountain View Cemetery in Reno.<ref>{{cite book |last=U.S. Congress |author-link= |date=August 6, 1959 |title=Report: Acceptance of Statue of Patrick A. McCarran |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0s0jAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA27-PA7 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=US Government Printing Office |page=7 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1903, McCarran married Harriet Martha \"Birdie\" Weeks (1882-1963).<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=Margaret>{{cite magazine |last=McCarran |first=Margaret Patricia |date=Fall-Winter 1968 |title=Patrick Anthony McCarran, 1876-1954 |url=http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210777-1968-3-4Fall-Winter.pdf |magazine=Nevada Historical Society Quarterly |location=Reno, NV |publisher=Nevada Historical Society |pages=5\u201353}}</ref>  They were the parents of four daughters and one son.<ref name=\"Dies\"/>  Samuel McCarran became a doctor and worked in Reno.<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>  Margaret and Mary became members of the [[Dominican Order#Sisters|Order of Dominican Sisters]].<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>  Norine was a longtime employee of the Library of Congress.<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>  Patricia became the wife of Edwin Parry Hay of Maryland.<ref name=\"Dies\"/><ref name=\"Margaret\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nMcCarran is remembered as one of the few Democrats to oppose President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and reject the [[New Deal]].<ref name=Pederson>{{cite book |last=Pederson |first=William D. |date=2006 |title=The FDR Years |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cv-kRJoXag4C&pg=PA177 |location=Facts on File |publisher=New York, NY |page=177 |isbn=978-0-8160-5368-1}}</ref> In addition, he was a proponent of the aviation industry; he was a sponsor of the [[Civil Aeronautics Act]] of 1938 and the Federal Airport Act of 1945, and was a proponent of establishing the [[United States Army Air Forces]] as the [[United States Air Force]] separate from the Army.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mccarran.com/NVAHOF/BiosTouchScreen/McCarran |title=Biography, HOF inductee Patrick A. McCarran |last=Nevada Aerospace Hall of Fame |website=Mccarran.com/NVAHOF/ |publisher=Clark County Department of Aviation |location=Las Vegas, NV |access-date=November 18, 2018}}</ref> He was also an ardent anti-Communist.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Carter |first1=Ralph G. |last2=Scott |first2= James M. |date=2009 |title=Choosing to Lead: Understanding Congressional Foreign Policy Entrepreneurs |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYzGTelSjcsC&pg=PA89 |location=Durham, NC |publisher=Duke University Press |page=89 |isbn=978-0-8223-4503-9 |author-link= }}</ref>\n\n[[Harold L. Ickes]] described McCarran as \"easy-going, old-shoe 'Pat'\" in a column criticizing McCarran as a tool of the oil companies, for not supporting certain regulations Ickes favored.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ickes |first=Harold |date=May 15, 1946 |title=Tidelands Should Not Worry Nevada Senator |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/104940193/ |work=[[The Indianapolis Star]] |location=Indianapolis, IN |page=12 |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> American journalist [[John Gunther]] was also critical of McCarran's alleged corporate ties, writing that he resembled gold \"in that he is soft, heavy, and not a good conductor.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Gunther|first=John|authorlink=John Gunther|title=Inside U.S.A.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/insideusa00guntrich/page/80 80], 84, 940|location=[[New York City|New York]]/[[London]]|publisher=[[Harper & Brothers]]|year=1947|title-link=Inside U.S.A. (book)}}</ref>\n\n[[File:U.S. Senator Pat McCarran handing mail bag to Pony Express rider, Dedication Ceremony, McCarran Air Field, Las Vegas, Nevada (74665).jpg|thumb|Postcard depicting McCarran at the dedication ceremony for the original McCarran Field, now [[Nellis Air Force Base]]]]\n[[McCarran International Airport]] located in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas, Nevada]] is named after Senator McCarran.<ref name=\"shaped\"/>  McCarran Boulevard in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] is named for Pat McCarran, as is McCarran Street in [[North Las Vegas, Nevada|North Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard N. |date=June 25, 2012 |title=Should McCarran airport be renamed for Las Vegas? |url=https://vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2012/jun/25/las-vegas-airport-needs-be-more-recognizable-outsi/ |newspaper=Vegas, Inc. |location=Las Vegas, NV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=John L. |date=August 28, 2012 |title=If we're erasing McCarran's name, maybe we should dump some others |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/john-l-smith/if-were-erasing-mccarrans-name-maybe-we-should-dump-some-others |newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal |location=Las Vegas, NV}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mccarran.jpg|thumb|left|[[Pat McCarran (Jacobson)|Statue]] in the National Statuary Hall Collection]]\nA [[Pat McCarran (Jacobson)|statue of McCarran]] is included in the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]] at the [[United States Capitol]].<ref name=\"shaped\"/>  Each state is allowed to display likenesses of two individuals; Nevada's are those of McCarran and [[Sarah Winnemucca]].<ref name=\"shaped\"/>\n\n===Possible statue removal===\nIn 2017, Nevada's three Democratic members of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] wrote to Governor [[Brian Sandoval]] and state legislative leaders and stated their view that review of McCarran's career might warrant removal of his statue from the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaley|first=Sean|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/nevada/nevada-lawmakers-favor-removing-mccarran-statue-us-capitol-poll|title=Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue from US Capitol|website=Reviewjournal.com|date=October 11, 2016|accessdate=January 12, 2017|ref={{sfnRef|\"Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue\"}}}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|While he fought for workers' rights and helped shape the country's aviation industry, McCarran left a legacy of racism, xenophobia and anti-Semitism, said the letter sent Tuesday by Reps. Dina Titus, Ruben Kihuen and Jacky Rosen.{{sfn|\"Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue\"}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Mel Lipman|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2012/sep/16/mccarrans-name-dishonors-nevada|title=McCarran's name dishonors Nevada - Las Vegas Sun News|website=Lasvegassun.com|accessdate=January 12, 2017|ref={{sfnRef|\"McCarran's name dishonors Nevada\"}}|date=September 16, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nOn January 11, 2017, it was reported that a poll of Nevada legislators indicated support for removing McCarran's statue from the collection.{{sfn|\"Nevada lawmakers favor removing McCarran statue\"}}  A bill introduced in the [[Nevada State Senate]], SB 174, which called for the removal of the statue and renaming of [[McCarran International Airport]] for former U.S. Senator [[Harry Reid]], failed to be passed before the end of the 2017 legislative session on June 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaley |first=Sean |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/2017-legislature/las-vegas-airport-will-not-get-a-name-change/ |title=Las Vegas airport will not get a name change \u2013 Las Vegas Review-Journal |publisher=Reviewjournal.com |date=June 6, 2017 |accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\n*Cartoonist [[Walt Kelly]] introduced a character into his ''[[Pogo (comic strip)|Pogo]]'' comic strip called Mole MacCaroney. Mole's near-blindness and concerns about \"germs\" were seen as a reference to McCarran and his immigration restriction policies.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dave in Northridge |date=November 28, 2012 |title=Top Comments: Okefenokee Swamp Edition |url= |newspaper=Daily Kos}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Black |first=James Eric |date=2016 |title=Walt Kelly and Pogo: The Art of the Political Swamp |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=umlECwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199 |location=Jefferson, NC |publisher=McFarland & Company |page=199 |isbn=978-0-7864-7987-0}}</ref>\n*McCarran was in part the inspiration for the fictional character of the corrupt United States Senator [[Pat Geary]] in the film ''[[The Godfather Part II]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=G.D. Spradlin, 1920-2011|url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-07-26/ae/29817237_1_spradlin-single-movie-geary|accessdate=December 23, 2011|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=July 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hoffman |first=Dave |date=March 6, 2007 |title=The Godfather's Connection to the US Attorney Scandal |url=https://concurringopinions.com/archives/2007/03/a_blast_from_th.html |newspaper=Concurring Opinions}}</ref>\n*McCarran's chair from his tenure in the U.S. Senate was featured on an episode of the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] reality television series ''[[Pawn Stars]]''.<ref>[[List of Pawn Stars episodes#Season 3|A listing of Season 3 episodes with synopses of the '''History''' channel reality TV series ''Pawn Stars'']]</ref>\n*In the video game, ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]'', the post-apocalyptic remains of [[McCarran International Airport]] have been turned into a New California Republic military base named Camp McCarran.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.falloutnewvegastour.com/2011/04/location-18-camp-mccarran.html |title=Fallout New Vegas Tour: Location 18; Camp McCarran |last=Worth |first=Chris |date=April 14, 2011 |website=Fallout: New Vegas Tour |publisher=Chris Worth}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1950\u201399)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Klingaman\n  | first = William\n  | title = The Encyclopedia of the McCarthy Era\n  | publisher = New York : Facts on File\n  | year = 1996\n  | isbn = 0-8160-3097-9\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofmc0000klin\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Ybarra\n  | first = Michael J.\n  | title = Washington Gone Crazy: Senator Pat McCarran and the Great American Communist Hunt\n  | publisher = Steerforth Publishing\n  | year = 2004\n  | isbn = 1-58642-065-8\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/washingtongonecr0000ybar\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Newman\n  | first = Robert P.\n  | title = Owen Lattimore And The \"Loss\" of China\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/owenlattimorelos0000newm\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = Berkeley : University of California Press\n  | year = 1992\n  | isbn = 0-520-07388-6}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last =Schrecker\n  | first =Ellen\n  | title =No Ivory Tower : McCarthyism and the Universities\n  | publisher =New York : Oxford University Press\n  | year =1986\n  | isbn =0-19-503557-7\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/noivorytowermcca00schr\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last =Schrecker\n  | first =Ellen\n  | title =Many Are The Crimes : McCarthyism In America\n  | publisher =Boston; London : Little, Brown\n  | year =1998\n  | isbn =0-316-77470-7\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/manyarecrimesmcc00schr\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  | last =Hopkins\n  | first = A. D.\n  | title = Pat McCarran, Perennial Politician\n  | work = The First 100; Portraits of the Men and Women Who Shaped Las Vegas\n  | publisher = Stephens Media Group\n  | year = 1999\n  | url = http://www.1st100.com/part2/mccarran.html\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  | title = \tPatrick McCarran (1876&ndash;1954)\n  | work = Las Vegas: An Unconventional History\n  | publisher = American Experience, PBS\n  | year = 2005\n  | url = https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/lasvegas/peopleevents/p_mccarran.html\n }}\n\n===By Pat McCarran===\n*{{cite book\n  | last = McCarran\n  | first = Pat\n  | title = Three years of the Federal Administrative Procedure Act: A study in Legislation\n  | publisher = Georgetown Law Journal Association\n  | year =1950\n  | id =  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = McCarran\n  | first = Pat\n  | title = Build the West to Build the Nation; Address Before Guests And Members of the Board of Trustees of Builders of the West, Inc.\n }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = McCarran\n  | first = Pat\n  | title = Displaced Persons: Facts Versus Fiction\n  | publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office\n  }}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|M000308}}\n*{{Findagrave|7125891}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Pat McCarran}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box|\n before=[[Tasker Oddie]]|\n state=Nevada|class=3|\n after=[[Ernest S. Brown]]|\n years=1933\u20131954\n|alongside=[[Key Pittman]], [[Berkeley L. Bunker]],<br>[[James G. Scrugham]], [[Edward P. Carville]], [[George W. Malone]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Colum