{"title_page": "Sergio Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1983)", "text_new": "{{other people|Sergio Garc\u00eda}}\n{{For|another Spanish footballer|Sergio Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1989)}}\n{{Spanish name|Garc\u00eda|De la Fuente}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Sergio Garc\u00eda\n| image = Sergio Garcia - Catalunya (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Garc\u00eda playing for [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] in 2013\n| fullname = Sergio Garc\u00eda de la Fuente\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|6|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| height = 1.74m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]] / [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1989\u20131993 | youthclubs1 = Bon Pastor\n| youthyears2 = 1993\u20131995 | youthclubs2 = [[CF Damm|Damm]]\n| youthyears3 = 1995\u20132002 | youthclubs3 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| youthyears4 = 1997\u20131999 | youthclubs4 = \u2192 [[CF Damm|Damm]] (loan)\n| years1 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs1 = [[FC Barcelona C|Barcelona C]] | caps1 = 22 | goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs2 = [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]] | caps2 = 60 | goals2 = 34\n| years3 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs3 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps3 = 4 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Levante UD|Levante]] (loan) | caps4 = 31 | goals4 = 7\n| years5 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs5 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps5 = 90 | goals5 = 14\n| years6 = 2008\u20132010 | clubs6 = [[Real Betis|Betis]] | caps6 = 62 | goals6 = 21\n| years7 = 2010\u20132015 | clubs7 = [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] | caps7 = 145 | goals7 = 41\n| years8 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs8 = [[Al-Rayyan SC|Al-Rayyan]] | caps8 = 49 | goals8 = 27\n| years9 = 2017\u20132019 | clubs9 = [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] | caps9 = 62 | goals9 = 4\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1999 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2001 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]] | nationalcaps2 = 3 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 9 | nationalgoals3 = 7\n| nationalyears4 = 2003 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]] | nationalcaps4 = 11 | nationalgoals4 = 7\n| nationalyears5 = 2004\u20132005 | nationalteam5 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps5 = 11 | nationalgoals5 = 4\n| nationalyears6 = 2008 | nationalteam6 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps6 = 2 | nationalgoals6 = 0\n| nationalyears7 = 2003\u2013 | nationalteam7 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] | nationalcaps7 = 15 | nationalgoals7 = 9\n| club-update = 18 May 2019\n| nationalteam-update = 25 March 2019\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008 Austria\u2013Switzerland]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Sergio Garc\u00eda de la Fuente''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8se\u027exjo \u0263a\u027e\u02c8\u03b8i.a}};{{efn-ua|In isolation, ''Garc\u00eda'' is pronounced {{IPA-es|\u0261a\u027e\u02c8\u03b8i.a|}}.}} born 9 June 1983) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Mainly a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], he can also appear as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]], preferably on the right.\n\nAfter starting out at [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], he went on to represent mainly [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] and [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]], serving as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of the latter. Over 14 seasons, he amassed [[La Liga]] totals of 360 matches and 75 goals.\n\nGarc\u00eda appeared for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] at [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], winning the tournament.\n\n==Club career==\n===Barcelona===\nBorn in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Garc\u00eda rose through the ranks of [[FC Barcelona]], finding however opportunities almost non-existent in the senior squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/story?id=503062|title=Debe ser el n\u00famero 23|trans-title=Must be number 23|publisher=[[ESPN Deportes]]|language=Spanish|date=18 November 2006|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> A frequent goalscorer for [[FC Barcelona B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], he made his first-team debut on 29 October 2002, coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Geovanni]] for the final 28 minutes of a 2\u20130 away win against [[Club Brugge KV]] in [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League group stage|the season]]'s [[UEFA Champions League]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/matches/round=1636/match=1036510/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Barcelona dent Brugge hopes|publisher=UEFA|date=29 October 2002|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> he made another cameo in that competition the following 19 March, in a 2\u20130 victory at [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for the second group phase.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/mar/19/minutebyminute.sport1|title=Newcastle 0\u20132 Barcelona|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last=Glendenning|first=Barry|date=19 March 2003|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2003, Garc\u00eda started in his [[La Liga]] debut in his first match at the [[Camp Nou]], a 1\u20131 draw against [[Sevilla FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2003/09/03/liga/1062548963.html|title=Ronaldinho da sentido a la 'madrug\u00e1' catalana|trans-title=Ronaldinho gives meaning to the Catalan 'early getup'|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|date=3 September 2003|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> On 1 March of the following year, he signed a three-year contract extension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=150536.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda signs new deal|publisher=UEFA|date=1 March 2004|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda was loaned to [[Levante UD]] on 21 July 2004, ahead of the [[2004\u201305 La Liga|upcoming top flight campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.levanteud.com/es/info/sergio-garcia-jugara-en-el-levante-ud-esta-temporada|title=Sergio Garcia jugar\u00e1 en el Levante UD esta temporada|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda will play for Levante UD this season|publisher=Levante UD|language=Spanish|date=21 July 2004|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the competition on 3 October to complete a 2\u20130 win over [[RCD Mallorca]] at the ''[[Estadi Ciutat de Val\u00e8ncia]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2004/10/03/liga/1096824015.html|title=El Levante cumple ante su afici\u00f3n tras vencer al Mallorca|trans-title=Levante get job done in front of their fans by beating Mallorca|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=3 October 2004|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> ranking team top scorer as the [[Valencian Community|Valencians]] were relegated; his last goal came on 5 May 2004 in a 1\u20133 away loss to [[Albacete Balompi\u00e9]], where he was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] moments later for fighting with [[Santiago Denia|Santi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2005/05/08/liga/1115572812.html|title=El Albacete condena al Levante a sufrir hasta el final|trans-title=Albacete condemn Levante to suffer until the end|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=8 May 2005|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Zaragoza===\nGarcia played all 38 matches for [[Real Zaragoza]] in [[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]], as they were eventually relegated from the top level. At the beginning of [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following season]], he was linked with a number of [[Premier League]] clubs including [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], along with teammate [[Diego Milito]]. Rumours that he would leave Zaragoza had been further fuelled after the club's relegation, as he was thrown out of a side pre-season training session by manager [[Marcelino Garc\u00eda Toral]] and was then left out of their opening day defeat against Levante.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.periodistadigital.com/deportes/object.php?o=958682|title=Marcelino echa del entrenamiento a Sergio Garc\u00eda|trans-title=Marcelino throws Sergio Garc\u00eda out of training session|publisher=Periodista Digital|language=Spanish|date=4 August 2008|accessdate=3 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Betis===\nOn 1 September 2008, in the dying seconds of the [[transfer window]], after continuous rumours, Garc\u00eda signed for [[Real Betis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=745274.html|title=Betis build with Sergio Garc\u00eda|publisher=UEFA|date=2 September 2008|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/1a_division/betis/es/desarrollo/1160906.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda: \"Poco a poco se puede estar m\u00e1s arriba\"|trans-title=Garc\u00eda: \"Little by little we can move up in the ranks\"|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=3 September 2008|accessdate=3 September 2008}}</ref> for a fee close to [[Euro|\u20ac]]10 million. He scored his first goal for his new club on 27 September in the team's home game against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] (1\u20132 loss), following up on his own saved [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252800?cc=5739|title=Real Betis 1\u20132 Real Madrid|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=27 September 2008|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> On 16 November he netted a brace in at 3\u20131 home win over [[Racing de Santander]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/253111?cc=5739|title=Real Betis 3\u20131 Racing Santander|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=16 November 2008|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> and, on 18 January of the following year, added another in the 3\u20131 success at [[Real Valladolid]] in which he also [[Assist (football)|assisted]] the other goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/253072?cc=5739|title=Valladolid 1\u20133 Real Betis|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=18 January 2009|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda was sent off three times in the first half of [[2008\u201309 La Liga|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/722/la-liga/2008/09/27/885165/madrid-sting-betis-with-late-ruud-strike|title=Madrid sting Betis with late Ruud strike|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=27 September 2008|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/722/la-liga/2008/11/02/945215/depor-shock-betis-for-first-away-win|title=Depor shock Betis for first away win|publisher=Goal|date=2 November 2008|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> On 7 February 2009, he helped Betis achieve a landmark victory at neighbouring Sevilla, scoring in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/253061?cc=5739|title=Sevilla FC 1\u20132 Real Betis|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=7 February 2009|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> In form, he was struck with a knee injury after celebrating his goal against [[CD Numancia]], a 3\u20133 home draw on 4 April,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252763?cc=5739|title=Real Betis 3\u20133 Numancia|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=4 April 2009|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/2009/04/05/futbol/equipos/betis/1238926670.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda se lesiona celebrando un gol|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda injures himself celebrating a goal|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=5 April 2009|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref> eventually missing a month of competition \u2013 with the team struggling during this time \u2013 and eventually dropping down a level at the end.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/2009/05/31/futbol/1adivision/1243796737.html|title=La monta\u00f1a rusa del descenso acaba con el Betis|trans-title=The relegation roller coaster finishes Betis|newspaper=Marca|last=Rinc\u00f3n|first=Jaime|language=Spanish|date=31 May 2009|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda scored 12 goals in the [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2009\u201310 campaign]], but the [[Andalusia]]ns failed to win promotion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sevilla.abc.es/deportes/alfinaldelapalmera/noticias/real-betis/pasado-presente-futuro-gol-del-betis-139253-1509054924.html|title=Pasado, presente y futuro en el gol del Betis|trans-title=Past, present and future in Betis' goal|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|last=Arbide|first=Juan|language=Spanish|date=27 October 2017|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Espanyol===\nIn August 2010, Garc\u00eda signed a five-year contract with [[RCD Espanyol]], moving to the club as a replacement to veteran [[Ra\u00fal Tamudo]] who left after nearly 20 years of service. He did not score in his first 15 games for [[Mauricio Pochettino]]'s team, ending the drought on 9 January 2011 when as a substitute he concluded a 4\u20130 home win over former team Zaragoza, assisted by his namesake [[Luis Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1981)|Luis]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2011/01/10/deportes/1294614013_850215.html|title=El Espanyol baila al Zaragoza|trans-title=Espanyol dance against Zaragoza|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Quixano|first=Jordi|language=Spanish|date=10 January 2011|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2013, Garc\u00eda scored his first hat-trick for the ''Pericos'' in a 4\u20131 win at [[Rayo Vallecano]] \u2013 two of his three goals came from the penalty spot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/futbol/20131124/54394465659/espanyol-golea-rayo-triplete-sergio-garcia.html|title=El Espanyol golea al Rayo con un triplete de Sergio Garc\u00eda|trans-title=Espanyol thrash Rayo with a hat-trick from Sergio Garc\u00eda|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish|date=24 November 2013|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> [[2014\u201315 La Liga|The following season]], he netted a career-best (in Spain) 14 league goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/05/10/futbol/equipos/espanyol/1431253071.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda, de leyenda|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda, like a legend|newspaper=Marca|last=Torres|first=Mari Carmen|language=Spanish|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Al-Rayyan===\nGarc\u00eda turned down an offer to join Qatar's [[Al Sadd SC]], who had recently signed Barcelona's [[Xavi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/rcd-espanyol/20150527/20255734557/sergio-garcia-da-marcha-atras-y-dice-no-al-futbol-qatari.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda da marcha atr\u00e1s y dice \u2018no\u2019 al f\u00fatbol qatar\u00ed|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda makes a U-turn and says 'no' to Qatari football|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=Ju\u00e1rez|first=Mar\u00eda Carmen|language=Spanish|date=27 May 2015|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> On 29 June, however, he joined [[Al-Rayyan SC]] in the same country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdespanyol.com/principal.php?modulo=detalleNoticia&idnoticia=20146&idmenu=9|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda marxar\u00e0 al Qatar|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda will go to Qatar|publisher=RCD Espanyol|language=Catalan|date=29 June 2015|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on 11 September, starting in a 4\u20130 [[Qatar Stars League|Stars League]] home win against [[Al-Sailiya SC]], and scored his first goal on 2 October when he confirmed a 2\u20130 victory over [[Al-Mesaimeer Sports Club]] at the [[Thani bin Jassim Stadium]]; on 22 November, he scored twice and assisted one of [[Rodrigo Tabata]]'s four goals in a league record 9\u20130 rout at [[Qatar SC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gulf-times.com/story/463872/Al-Rayyan-thrash-Qatar-SC-9-0-to-register-record-w|title=Al Rayyan thrash Qatar SC 9\u20130 to register record win|newspaper=[[Gulf Times]]|date=22 November 2015|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2016, Garc\u00eda netted once in a 5\u20130 win at [[Al-Wakrah Sport Club]] that handed his team [[2015\u201316 Qatar Stars League|their first league title]] in 21 years, and with five games to spare.<ref name=QFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.qfa.com.qa/al-rayyan-crowned-qsl-champions-end-21-years-wait/|title=Al Rayyan crowned QSL champions, end 21 years wait|publisher=[[Qatar Football Association]]|date=5 March 2016|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Espanyol return===\nOn 16 June 2017, aged 34, Garc\u00eda returned to Espanyol after agreeing to a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcdespanyol.com/es/actualidad/vuelve-sergio-garcia/_n:5228/|title=\u00a1Vuelve Sergio Garc\u00eda!|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda returns!|publisher=RCD Espanyol|language=Spanish|date=16 June 2017|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> Exactly two years later, he left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-espana.net/78741/sergio-garcia-leaves-espanyol|title=Sergio Garcia leaves Espanyol|publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a|last=Brennan|first=Feargal|date=16 June 2019|accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Sergio Garc\u00eda Catalunya.jpg|thumb|Garc\u00eda in action for [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in January 2013.]]\nGarc\u00eda was part of the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain under-19]] team that won the [[2002 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2002 UEFA European Championship]] in Norway, equalising in the 3\u20131 win over [[Slovakia national under-19 football team|Slovakia]] in their final group game in [[Drammen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2002/07/25/futbol/1027623801.html|title=Espa\u00f1a se mete en la final de la mano de Fernando Torres|trans-title=Spain advance to the finals at the hand of Fernando Torres|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=26 July 2002|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> On 22 October 2003, against [[Slovakia national under-20 football team|the same country]] but at [[Spain national under-20 football team|under-20 level]], he netted a hat-trick in a 4\u20130 win in preparation for the [[2003 FIFA World Youth Championship|FIFA World Youth Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2003/10/22/mas_futbol/1066773625_850215.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda da el triunfo|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda gives triumph|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=22 October 2003|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> During the tournament in the [[United Arab Emirates]], he scored against [[Mali national under-20 football team|Mali]] in the group and netted the only goal against [[Paraguay national under-20 football team|Paraguay]] in the [[Single-elimination tournament|last 16]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eluniverso.com/2003/12/09/0001/15/063783EE81344602B20494F83DCB30FD.html|title=Espa\u00f1a se clasifica al vencer 1\u20130 a Paraguay|trans-title=Spain qualify by beating Paraguay 1\u20130|newspaper=El Universo|language=Spanish|date=9 December 2003|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> as the nation finished as runners-up.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under19/news/newsid=134957.html|title=Spain denied at final hurdle|publisher=UEFA|date=19 December 2003|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nWithout having been previously [[Cap (sport)|capped]], Garc\u00eda made the [[Spain national football team|Spanish]] final squad-of-23 for [[UEFA Euro 2008]] (which Spain went on to win) as a replacement for Barcelona's [[Bojan Krki\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/476/euro-2008/2008/05/17/699623/ra%C3%BAl-out-sergio-garc%C3%ADa-in-spain-euro-2008-squad|title=Ra\u00fal out, Sergio Garc\u00eda in Spain Euro 2008 squad|publisher=Goal|last=Macdonald|first=Ewan|date=17 May 2008|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for the national side on 31 May 2008, coming on as an 83rd-minute substitute for [[David Silva]] in a 2\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win against [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in [[Huelva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huelvainformacion.es/article/deportes/143381/espanaperu/ensayo/poco/convincente.html|title=Espa\u00f1a-Per\u00fa (2\u20131): Un ensayo poco convincente|trans-title=Spain-Peru (2\u20131): A hardly convincing trial|publisher=Huelva Informaci\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=1 June 2008|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June, Garc\u00eda earned his first competitive [[Cap (sport)|cap]], playing for the full 90 minutes against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] in Spain's third and final [[UEFA Euro 2008 Group D|group D game]] in Euro 2008: in the 88th minute, he delivered a pinpoint left-footed cross for [[Dani G\u00fciza]] to head home the 2\u20131 winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363473.stm|title=Russia 2\u20130 Sweden & Greece 1\u20132 Spain|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|last=McKenzie|first=Andrew|date=18 June 2008|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nGarc\u00eda also represented Spain at all [[Spain national football team|youth levels]], as well as appearing frequently for the [[Catalonia national football team|unofficial Catalan national team]]. On 22 December 2009, he scored the side's first goal in a 4\u20132 defeat of [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] and, on 30 December 2013, he netted twice in a 4\u20131 victory over [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/catalonia-cape-verde-catalonia-claim-victory-with-eight-fc-barcelona-players-4-1|title=Catalonia \u2013 Cape Verde: Catalonia claim victory with eight FC Barcelona players (4\u20131)|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=30 December 2013|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref> In March 2019, he played his 16th game against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] in [[Girona]], and surpassed [[Sergio (footballer, born 1976)|Sergio Gonz\u00e1lez]] as the most capped player in its history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmon.cat/monesport/catalunya/sergio-garcia-fa-historia-amb-la-seleccio-catalana_406149102.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda fa hist\u00f2ria amb la selecci\u00f3 catalana|trans-title=Sergio Garc\u00eda makes history with the Catalan national team|newspaper=El M\u00f3n|last=Melgar|first=Blai|language=Catalan|date=25 March 2019|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|18 May 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] \n|[[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u201303]]<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j2490.html|title=Sergio Garc\u00eda: Sergio Garc\u00eda de la Fuente|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n|rowspan=2|[[La Liga]]\n|0||0||0||0||2{{efn|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]|name=UCL}}||0||2||0\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u201304]]<ref name=\"BD\"/>\n|4||0||2||0||1{{efn|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]|name=UC}}||0||7||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!4||0||2||0||3||0||9||0\n|-\n|[[Levante UD|Levante]] (loan)\n|[[2004\u201305 La Liga|2004\u201305]]<ref name=\"BD\"/>\n|La Liga\n|31||7||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||32||7\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] \n|[[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u201306]]<ref name=\"BD\"/>\n|rowspan=3|La Liga\n|19||4||6||0||colspan=2|\u2014||25|