{"title_page": "J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez\n| image = J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = M\u00e9nez playing for [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] in 2016\n| fullname = J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=526&kisiId=2017828 |title=Jeremy Menez |publisher=Turkish Football Federation |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|5|7|df=y}}<ref name=Lequipe>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur20434.html |title=J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez |newspaper=L'\u00c9quipe |location=Paris |accessdate=20 January 2020 |language=French}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Longjumeau]], France\n| height = 1.83 m<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clubamerica.com.mx/jugador/jeremy-menez/|title=Club Am\u00e9rica|first=Club|last=Am\u00e9rica|publisher=clubamerica.com.mx}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]] / [[Forward (association football)#Winger|Winger]]\n| currentclub = [[Paris FC]]\n| clubnumber = 39\n| youthyears1 = 1994\u20131995\n| youthclubs1 = CA Vitry\n| youthyears2 = 1995\u20132000\n| youthclubs2 = CFF Paris\n| youthyears3 = 2000\u20132001\n| youthclubs3 = CSF Br\u00e9tigny\n| youthyears4 = 2001\u20132004\n| youthclubs4 = [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs1 = [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]]\n| caps1 = 55\n| goals1 = 7\n| years2 = 2006\u20132008\n| clubs2 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n| caps2 = 57\n| goals2 = 14\n| years3 = 2008\u20132011\n| clubs3 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n| caps3 = 84\n| goals3 = 7\n| years4 = 2011\u20132014\n| clubs4 = [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]\n| caps4 = 79\n| goals4 = 14\n| years5 = 2014\u20132016\n| clubs5 = [[A.C. Milan]]\n| caps5 = 43\n| goals5 = 18\n| years6 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs6 = [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]]\n| caps6 = 26\n| goals6 = 3\n| years7 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs7 = [[Antalyaspor]]\n| caps7 = 7\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs8 = [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]\n| caps8 = 18\n| goals8 = 5\n| years9 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs9 = [[Paris FC]]\n| caps9 = 17\n| goals9 = 4\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132003\n| nationalteam1 = [[France national under-16 football team|France U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 14\n| nationalgoals1 = 12\n| nationalyears2 = 2003\u20132004\n| nationalteam2 = [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 17\n| nationalgoals2 = 6\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\n| nationalteam3 = [[France national under-18 football team|France U18]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 6\n| nationalgoals3 = 6\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\u20132006\n| nationalteam4 = [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 9\n| nationalgoals4 = 3\n| nationalyears5 = 2008\n| nationalteam5 = [[France national under-21 football team|France U21]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 3\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| nationalyears6 = 2010\u20132013\n| nationalteam6 = [[France national football team|France]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 24\n| nationalgoals6 = 2\n| club-update = 23:50, 2 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0292e.\u0281e.mi me.n\u025bz}}; born 7 May 1987) is a French professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for French club [[Paris FC]]. M\u00e9nez has been described as an ambidextrous, [[Dribbling#Association football|technically skilled]], pacy [[playmaker]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.maxifoot.fr/football/article-1640.htm | title = M\u00e9nez, le prodige |date=25 January 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Maxifoot | language = French}}</ref>\n\nM\u00e9nez began his career spending time with various clubs in the [[\u00cele-de-France (region)|\u00cele-de-France]] [[Regions of France|region]] such as the Centre de Formation de Paris and CSF Br\u00e9tigny. In 2001, he secured a move to [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]] and spent four years in the club's youth academy. In March 2004, M\u00e9nez became the youngest professional football player in the history of [[Ligue 1]] after signing a professional contract and made his professional debut in the [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305 season]]. With Sochaux, he played [[UEFA|European]] football for the first time after participating in the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Cup|2004\u201305 edition]] of the [[UEFA Cup]]. After two seasons at the club, he joined [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]. At Monaco, M\u00e9nez developed into a playmaking midfielder under the tutelage of Brazilian manager [[Ricardo Gomes]]. After two successful seasons in [[Monaco]], he signed for [[Serie A]] club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] on a four-year contract. With Roma, M\u00e9nez featured in the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the first time and scored 12 goals in over 100 appearances with the club. In July 2011, after three seasons with Roma, M\u00e9nez returned to France signing a three-year contract with [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]. He was then signed by [[A.C. Milan]] on a free transfer in June 2014, signing a three-year contract.\n\nM\u00e9nez is a former [[France national youth football team|French youth international]] and has represented his nation at every level for which he was eligible. Prior to playing for the [[France national football team|senior team]], he played in the [[France national under-17 football team|under-17 team]] that won the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship]]. M\u00e9nez made his [[France national football team|senior]] international debut in August 2010 in a friendly match against [[Norway national football team|Norway]]. He represented his country at the [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nM\u00e9nez was born in [[Longjumeau]], Essonne.<ref name=Lequipe/> As a child, he grew up in [[Vitry-sur-Seine]], not far from his birthplace, and supported hometown club [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref name=\"menez_early\">{{cite news |url=http://www.omarlecheri.net/tandem6/Menez.htm |title=J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez: de Vitry \u00e0 Monaco |date=8 March 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Omar Le Cherie |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216035150/http://www.omarlecheri.net/tandem6/Menez.htm |archivedate=16 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> M\u00e9nez became attracted to football through his father and older brother who were football players themselves. M\u00e9nez began his career at local club CA Vitry. After a year at the club, M\u00e9nez joined the Centre de Formation de Paris, a youth sporting club designed to cater only to football players under the age of 19.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cffp.fr/accueilcffp_histoireducffp.htm |title=Histoire du CFFP |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Centre de Formation de Paris |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720210916/http://www.cffp.fr/accueilcffp_histoireducffp.htm |archivedate=20 July 2011 }}</ref> While at C.F.F.P, M\u00e9nez developed and honed his technical skills and was placed into the [[playmaker]] position by his coaches. After five years at the academy, he departed the club after developing friction with the academy coaches.<ref name =\"menez_early\"/> After leaving CFFP, M\u00e9nez joined CSF Br\u00e9tigny, a local Parisian club that also trained [[France national football team|French internationals]] [[Patrice Evra]] and [[Jimmy Briand]]. He spent only a year at the club before securing a move to professional club [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]] in Franche-Comt\u00e9.\n\n===Sochaux===\nUpon his arrival at Sochaux, M\u00e9nez entered the club's youth academy and began attending the sports department's elite high school, Vignes de Seloncourt, with ambitions of becoming an accountant.<ref name =\"menez_way\">{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=275245.html | title = M\u00e9nez shows Sochaux the way |date= 28 January 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]]}}</ref> While in the club's academy, M\u00e9nez was adept both on and off the field earning good grades in school.<ref name =\"menez_early\"/> On 24 March 2004, at the age of 16, he signed his first professional contract with Sochaux, agreeing to a three-year deal until June 2007. Upon signing the contract, he became the youngest professional football player in the history of [[Ligue 1]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football365.fr/france/infos-clubs/sochaux/article_27532_Sochaux-Jeremy-Menez-passe-pro.shtml | title = Sochaux: J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez passe pro |date= 24 March 2004 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Football 365 | language = French}}</ref> M\u00e9nez was subsequently promoted to the club's senior team and assigned the number 26 shirt by manager [[Guy Lacombe]]. Prior to signing his contract, M\u00e9nez drew strong interest from English clubs [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. The latter club's manager at the time, [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]], was later accused by Sochaux's former president [[Jean-Claude Plessis]] of [[tapping up]] M\u00e9nez; he accused Ferguson of meeting with the player's parents in Paris and offering them financial favours. Manchester United denied the accusations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={04B0BD8D-A3EC-4900-A6D6-69EC18C57BB0}&newsid=144864&page=1 |title=Fergie in \"tap\" row |date=25 January 2005 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=[[Manchester United F.C.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925034142/http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid=%7B04B0BD8D-A3EC-4900-A6D6-69EC18C57BB0%7D&newsid=144864&page=1 |archive-date=25 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> M\u00e9nez travelled to [[Manchester]] and visited the team's facilities and [[Old Trafford]], the club's stadium, before deciding to remain in France.<ref name=\"menez_way\"/>\n\nOn 7 August 2004, M\u00e9nez made his professional debut in the club's opening match of the [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305 season]] against [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]]. He started the match and played 57 minutes before being substituted for in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2004/2005&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=9 |title=Sochaux v. Ajaccio Match Report |date=7 August 2004 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Despite being so young, M\u00e9nez was a regular within the team, often rotating between the bench and starting XI. On 20 November, he scored his first professional goal in a 3\u20131 victory over [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2004/2005&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J15&num_ordre=5 |title=Monaco v. Sochaux Match Report |date=20 November 2004 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Two months later, M\u00e9nez became the youngest player in league history to score a [[hat-trick]] after recording one in the team's 4\u20130 victory over [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]].<ref name=\"menez_way\"/> He scored the goals in a seven-minute span to assure Sochaux of victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2004/2005&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J22&num_ordre=9 |title=Sochaux v. Bordeaux Match Report |date=22 January 2005 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> M\u00e9nez was a regular during the team's [[2004\u201305 UEFA Cup]] campaign, appearing in six matches with the club.<ref name=uc0405>{{cite web|title=J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez profile|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=72715/profile/index.html|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> Sochaux suffered elimination in the Round of 32 at the hands of Greek club [[Olympiakos FC|Olympiakos]]. Following the season, M\u00e9nez was nominated for the [[National Union of Professional Football Players|UNFP]] [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Young Player of the Year|Young Player of the Year]] award but lost out to [[FC Nantes|Nantes]] [[midfielder]] [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my Toulalan]].\n\nFor the [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306 season]], M\u00e9nez switched to the number 11 shirt and was given a more prominent role within the team by new manager [[Dominique Bijotat]]. He appeared in 31 league matches, fifth-best on the team, and scored three goals. M\u00e9nez scored his first goal on 15 October 2005 in a 1\u20131 draw against Bordeaux.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2005/2006&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J11&num_ordre=2 |title=Bordeaux v. Sochaux Match Report |date=15 October 2005 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> At the beginning of the new year, M\u00e9nez scored his final two goals in another 1\u20131 draw with [[OGC Nice|Nice]] and a 4\u20130 victory over [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2005/2006&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J21&num_ordre=8 |title=Sochaux v. Nice Match Report |date=11 January 2006 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2005/2006&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J23&num_ordre=8 |title=Sochaux v. Saint-\u00c9tienne Match Report |date=21 January 2006 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Sochaux finished the season in a disappointing 15th position after finishing the four previous seasons in the top ten. This led M\u00e9nez to become unsettled and to declare his desire to leave the club. On 8 June 2006, Sochaux chairman Dassier announced that he would consider offers for the player with Ligue 1 clubs Paris Saint-Germain, Bordeaux, Monaco and English club Arsenal reported to be interested.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_2379703,00.html | title = Sochaux take M\u00e9nez stance |date= 8 June 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | language = French}}</ref>\n\n===Monaco===\nOn 22 June 2006, Sochaux announced on its website that it had reached an agreement with fellow Ligue 1 club Monaco for the transfer of M\u00e9nez. He signed a four-year contract, with the transfer fee undisclosed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/news/player_archive/0,19889,11816_1_123953_1,00.html | title = Monaco bag Menez |date= 22 June 2006| accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> M\u00e9nez was given the number 10 shirt by manager [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 B\u00f6l\u00f6ni]] and inserted into his preferred left-winger position. He made his club debut on 19 August in the team's 1\u20131 draw with [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]], appearing as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J03&num_ordre=7 |title=Rennes v. Monaco Match Report |date=19 August 2006 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061202170155/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006%2F2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J03&num_ordre=7 |archivedate=2 December 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 30 September, M\u00e9nez scored his first goal for the club in a 2\u20131 win over [[Le Mans FC|Le Mans]], netting the game-winner ten minutes from time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J08&num_ordre=5 |title=Monaco v. Le Mans Match Report |date=30 September 2006 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061203062121/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006%2F2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J08&num_ordre=5 |archivedate=3 December 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the firing of B\u00f6l\u00f6ni and the arrival of new manager [[Ricardo Gomes]], M\u00e9nez struggled to get consistent playing time and grew frustrated, which led to interest abroad from Manchester United and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11667_2792810,00.html | title = English giants track M\u00e9nez |date= 10 October 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> On 11 November, however, he was re-inserted into the starting line-up and scored the equalising goal in a 2\u20132 draw with Lorient.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J14&num_ordre=4 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061203041108/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006%2F2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J14&num_ordre=4 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 December 2006 |title=Monaco v. Lorient Match Report |date=18 November 2006 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French |df=dmy-all }}</ref> M\u00e9nez maintained his form into the new year, but struggled for fitness in February due to a [[groin]] injury. The injury required surgery and M\u00e9nez missed two months of play.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11800_3369880,00.html | title = M\u00e9nez scare for Monaco |date= 31 March 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> He returned to the team in April and scored goals in three-straight matches against [[Lille OSC|Lille]], [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]] and [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J33&num_ordre=4 |title=Monaco v. Lille Match Report |date=21 April 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J34&num_ordre=10 |title=Valenciennes v. Monaco Match Report |date=28 April 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J35&num_ordre=4 |title=Monaco v. Marseille Match Report |date=6 May 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> M\u00e9nez finished the 2006\u201307 campaign by scoring the only goal in a win over the champions [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J37&num_ordre=4 |title=Monaco v. Lyon Match Report |date=19 May 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDespite summer interest from English [[Premier League]] clubs, M\u00e9nez opted to remain at Monaco. In the [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308 campaign]], he scored his first goal in the team's 3\u20130 victory over his former club Sochaux.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11674_3961687,00.html | title = M\u00e9nez likely to stay put |date= 10 August 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J04&num_ordre=9 |title=Sochaux v. Monaco Match Report |date=18 August 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The following week, he netted again, this time in a 3\u20131 win over Le Mans.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J05&num_ordre=4 |title=Monaco v. Le Mans Match Report |date=25 August 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 15 December, M\u00e9nez scored a double in a 3\u20131 victory against [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J18&num_ordre=6 |title=Monaco v. Lens Match Report |date=15 December 2007 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was his first multi-goal game since his hat-trick three years prior. The following month, M\u00e9nez scored both of the team's goal in a 2\u20130 away win against [[FC Metz|Metz]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J21&num_ordre=6 |title=Metz v. Monaco Match Report |date=19 January 2008 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel |language=French }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 23 February 2008, he suffered an injury in a league match against Paris-Saint Germain, which led to him leaving the match at half-time. The injury was discovered to be serious and M\u00e9nez missed three months before returning for the final two matches of the season making obligatory substitute appearances.\n\n===Roma===\nAfter featuring in Monaco's first three league matches of the season, it was reported on 27 August 2008 that M\u00e9nez had signed a four-year contract with Italian club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]. The transfer fee was priced at \u20ac10.5&nbsp;million with Monaco set to receive another \u20ac1.5&nbsp;million in incentives.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11800_4057266,00.html | title = M\u00e9nez joins Roma |date=27 August 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> M\u00e9nez was announced as the replacement for departed wingers [[Mancini (Brazilian footballer)|Mancini]] and [[Ludovic Giuly]] and selected the number 24 shirt, the former number of club legend [[Marco Delvecchio]]. He made his debut for the club on 31 August in the team's [[Serie A]] match against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], appearing as a substitute in the 63rd minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251218&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = AS Roma 1 \u2013 1 Napoli |date=31 August 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> M\u00e9nez made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in the team's group stage match against Bordeaux, playing 51 minutes in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=254674&cc=5901&league=UEFA.CHAMPIONS | title = Baptista's deadly double |date=1 October 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 6 December, he scored his first goal for the club in a 1\u20130 victory over [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251392&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = Chievo Verona 0\u20131 AS Roma |date=6 December 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> For the majority of the campaign, however, M\u00e9nez struggled for consistent playing time, rarely lasting an entire match and often starting on the bench for consecutive matches under [[Luciano Spalletti]]. On 24 May 2009, he appeared as a substitute in the 75th minute against [[A.C. Milan]]. After five minutes on the field, M\u00e9nez scored a goal to put Roma up 2\u20131; the capital club went on to win the match 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251572&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = AS Roma 3\u20132 Torino |date=31 May 2009 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> The following week, he started the match and scored a goal in a 3\u20132 win over [[Torino F.C.|Torino]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251563&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = AC Milan 2\u20133 AS Roma |date=24 May 2009 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> He was later substituted out in the 59th minute.\n\nFor the [[2009\u201310 Serie A|2009\u201310 season]], M\u00e9nez switched to the unusual number 94 shirt. He scored against Milan his first goal on 18 October 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=278467&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = Pato seals nervy win for Milan |date=19 October 2009 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 6 January 2010, he drew the ire of new manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] and several teammates, who criticised him for his substitute appearance against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] in which he gave a somewhat lackadaisical effort. Following the criticism, M\u00e9nez stated, \"I touched the lowest point of my career in that game away to Cagliari,\" and, \"My teammates were right to criticise me.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football-italia.net/blogs/jh110.html | title = From a boy to M\u00e9nez |date=30 July 2010 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Football Italia }}</ref> On 11 January, M\u00e9nez issued an apology to coach Ranieri and his teammates and brushed off rumours of him issuing a transfer request by declaring himself fully committed to the team. On 30 January, [[midfielder]] [[Simone Perrotta]] stated that M\u00e9nez simply needed a confidence boost.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asromalive.com/perrotta-ranieri-nazionale-roma-jeremy-menez/19300/ | title = Perrotta: \"Ranieri, la Nazionale, la mia Roma e J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez: dico io\" |date=30 January 2010 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=AS Roma Live | language= Italian}}</ref> After appearing as a substitute for four consecutive matches after the Cagliari match, M\u00e9nez made his first start since December 2009 in a league match against [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] on 21 February. He capped the return by assisting on the game-winning goal scored by [[Mirko Vu\u010dini\u0107]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=278498&cc=5901 | title = AS Roma 1 \u2013 0 Catania |date=21 February 2010 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> M\u00e9nez finished the campaign by starting eight of the final ten league matches as Roma finished the season in second place and qualified for the [[UEFA Champions League]].\n\nIn the [[2010\u201311 Serie A|2010\u201311 season]], M\u00e9nez began the season as a starter under Ranieri after his successful end to the previous season. Despite being a starter, however, Ranieri continued to undermine M\u00e9nez's durability as he consistently substituted the player out in every match he started. On 3 November, M\u00e9nez scored his first goal of the campaign in a 3\u20132 Champions League victory over Swiss club [[FC Basel|Basel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000118/match=2002865/index.html | title = Roma hang on to make amends at Basel |date= 3 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref> A week later, he assisted on a [[Marco Borriello]] goal in a 3\u20132 win over [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304797&cc=5901 | title = AS Roma 3\u20132 Fiorentina |date= 10 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 13 November, for the first time in the season, M\u00e9nez played an entire match after playing in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304771&cc=5901 | title = Totti penalty earns draw |date= 13 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> In the team's next league match against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], he scored his first league goal and also assisted on a goal in a 2\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304782&cc=5901 | title = Roma up to third |date= 20 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> After going scoreless in December, on 22 January 2011, M\u00e9nez scored the final goal in a 3\u20130 win over Cagliari.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304777&cc=5901 | title = Ranieri's men put the pressure on Milan |date= 22 January 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 16 February, M\u00e9nez scored a goal in Roma's first leg of its Champions League first knockout round tie with [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000119/match=2003751/index.html | title = Shakhtar surge too much for Roma |date= 16 February 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref> Five days later, Ranieri resigned from his position as manager and replaced with [[Vincenzo Montella]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SPORT/football/02/20/football.italy.ranieri.roma/index.html | title = Ranieri quits as Roma coach after fourth successive defeat |date= 21 February 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 |publisher=CNN }}</ref> Under Montella, M\u00e9nez appeared in the manager's first three matches as a substitute. On 13 March, he made his first start under Montella in a league match against [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], but was substitute out after 55 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304900&cc=5901 | title = Totti brace seals derby win |date= 13 March 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 23 March, in an interview with French newspaper ''[[L'Equipe]]'', M\u00e9nez admitted that he was frustrated with his playing time under Montella.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/serie-a/news/detail/item600015/Menez-agent-reveals-Montella-problem/ |title=M\u00e9nez agent reveals Montella problem |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=26 April 2011 |publisher=ESPN |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120729041104/http://www.espnstar.com/football/serie-a/news/detail/item600015/Menez-agent-reveals-Montella-problem/ |archivedate=29 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The frustration reached its zenith when, on 21 April, M\u00e9nez and Montella got into an altercation during a morning training session after Montella reportedly \"spent a quarter of an hour berating the France international\" for his lack of commitment.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.corrieredellosport.it/calcio/serie_a/roma/2011/04/21-168038/Auto+Menez+danneggiata%3A+sassi+contro+il+parabrezza | title = Auto M\u00e9nez danneggiata: sassi contro il parabrezza | date = 21 April 2011 | accessdate = 26 April 2011 | publisher = [[Corriere dello Sport \u2013 Stadio]] | language = Italian | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121013232628/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/calcio/serie_a/roma/2011/04/21-168038/Auto+Menez+danneggiata:+sassi+contro+il+parabrezza | archivedate = 13 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.daily-calcio.com/index.php?option=news&task=viewarticle&sid=30861 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004143608/http://www.daily-calcio.com/index.php?option=news&task=viewarticle&sid=30861 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 October 2011 |title=Montella bust up with M\u00e9nez |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=26 April 2011 |publisher=Daily-Calcio }}</ref> Later that night, following the team's [[Coppa Italia]] tie with [[Inter Milan]], while leaving the [[Stadio Olimpico]] in his vehicle, M\u00e9nez was attacked by stone-throwing \"thugs\", which resulted in his car [[windshield]] being smashed.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/2011/04/21-120700/Roma%3A+sassi+contro+l%27auto+di+Menez | title = Roma: sassi contro l'auto di M\u00e9nez | date = 21 April 2011 | accessdate = 26 April 2011 | publisher = [[Tuttosport]] | language = Italian | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161019212009/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/2011/04/21-120700/Roma%3A+sassi+contro+l%27auto+di+Menez | archivedate = 19 October 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Paris Saint-Germain ===\n[[File:Menez et Kombouar\u00e9.png|thumb|200px|left|M\u00e9nez with manager [[Antoine Kombouar\u00e9]] in 2011.]]\n\nOn 25 July 2011, Paris Saint-Germain confirmed that the club had signed M\u00e9nez to a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2011/20110725_144853_matuidi-et-menez-au-psg-off.html | title = Matuidi et M\u00e9nez au PSG (off.) | date = 25 July 2011 | work = [[L'Equipe]] | accessdate = 25 July 2011 | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110804050117/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2011/20110725_144853_matuidi-et-menez-au-psg-off.html | archivedate = 4 August 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The transfer fee was \u20ac8&nbsp;million plus possible future incentives.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/soccer/wires/07/25/2080.ap.soc.psg.signings.2nd.ld.writethru.0394/ | title = PSG signs M\u00e9nez, Matuidi to spur title ambitions | date = 25 July 2011 |work=Sports Illustrated | accessdate =25 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://109.75.174.100/~asroma/downloads/corporate_investor/1311672014_260711_menez.pdf | title = Cessione a titolo definitivo dei diritti alle prestazioni sportive des calciatore J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez | date = 25 July 2011 | work = [[A.S. Roma]] | accessdate = 1 August 2011 | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/60ai3E1gF?url=http://109.75.174.100/~asroma/downloads/corporate_investor/1311672014_260711_menez.pdf | archivedate = 31 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He was presented to the media the same day \u2013 alongside fellow new signing and international teammate [[Blaise Matuidi]] \u2013 and was assigned the number 7 shirt.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.psg.fr/fr/Article/003001/Article/54398/Matuidi-et-Menez-s-engagent-avec-le-PSG | title = Matuidi et M\u00e9nez s'engagent avec le PSG | date = 25 July 2011 | work=[[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.]] | accessdate =25 July 2011 | language = French}}</ref> M\u00e9nez made his club debut for the team in its 1\u20130 defeat to the [[New York Red Bulls]] at the [[Emirates Cup]]. He made his competitive debut for PSG on 6 August 2011 in the team's opening 1\u20130 league defeat to [[FC Lorient|Lorient]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Paris Saint-Germain v. Lorient Match Report | url = http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/74378 | date = 6 August 2011 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | accessdate =18 August 2011 | language = French}}</ref> The following week, he assisted on the team's opening goal, scored by [[Kevin Gameiro]], in a 1\u20131 draw with Rennes.<ref>{{cite news | title = Rennes v. Paris Saint-Germain Match Report | url = http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/74384 | date = 13 August 2011 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | accessdate =18 August 2011 | language = French}}</ref> On 18 August 2011, in PSG's first leg [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] playoff round tie against Luxembourger club [[FC Differdange 03|Differdange]], M\u00e9nez scored the final goal for the team in a 4\u20130 away win. He also assisted on a goal in the victory.<ref>{{cite news | title = Differdange v. PSG Match Report | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000271/match=2007211/postmatch/index.html | date = 18 August 2011 | work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] | accessdate =18 August 2011 }}</ref> Three days later, he again assisted Gameiro for a goal in a 2\u20131 win over [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]], helping PSG earn its first league win of the season. On 28 August, M\u00e9nez netted his first league goal for the club away to [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]]; Paris Saint-Germain won the match 3\u20131.\n\nUnder the guidance of coaches [[Antoine Kombouar\u00e9]] and later [[Carlo Ancelotti]], M\u00e9nez enjoyed a strong campaign which saw him deliver seven goals and 12 assists in 33 league appearances for PSG, a career best for him. On 4 December 2011, during a 3\u20132 home league victory against [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]], M\u00e9nez scored PSG's 2,000th goal in top-flight football.\n\nIn the [[2012\u201313 Paris Saint-Germain F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]], M\u00e9nez was used less prolifically in [[2012\u201313 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] matches. With two goals and two assists in five European appearances, however, he has been one of his club's main actors in their Champions League efforts, developing a strong understanding on the pitch with new star striker [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]], another former Serie A player.\n\n===A.C. Milan===\n[[File:MenezMilan (cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|M\u00e9nez with [[A.C. Milan]] in 2015.]]\n\nIn June 2014, Italian club A.C. Milan confirmed that the club had signed M\u00e9nez on a three-year contract.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)--> On 31 August 2014, M\u00e9nez scored a penalty on his debut for Milan against Lazio. He went on to score two goals against [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] helping Milan win the game. His first goal in this game was from a penalty, and the second goal was a beautifully worked backheel finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/italian-serie-a/match/403818/parma-ac-milan/report |title=Jeremy Menez stars as AC Milan edge nine-goal thriller with Parma |work=ESPNFC |date=14 September 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2014 }}</ref> On 8 November, M\u00e9nez scored a penalty kick and assisted [[Stephan El Shaarawy]]'s goal as Milan drew [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] 2\u20132.\n\nOn 23 November, M\u00e9nez scored a beautiful goal as he calmy converted El Shaarawy's cross in the far net in the ''[[Derby della Madonnina]]'' against Inter. He then scored two goals and was named man of the match in the next game against Udinese. M\u00e9nez also continued his impressive form and scored a beautiful goal as he dribbled past 3 defenders and put it in the net as he helped Milan beat Napoli 2\u20130.<ref>http://www.whoscored.com/Players/10407/Fixtures/Jrmy-Menez</ref> M\u00e9nez scored two goals and created an assist in the 3\u20131 defeat of Parma on 1 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://footyroom.com/ac-milan-3-1-parma-2015-02/|title=VIDEO AC Milan 3 \u2013 1 Parma}}</ref> He followed this with a penalty in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]] on 7 March and a brace in a 3\u20131 defeat of Cagliari on 21 March, hitting a career high in goals for a single club (15, surpassing his previous best of 14 for PSG). On 4 March 2015, M\u00e9nez scored the winning goal after a long solo run against [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]] in a 2\u20131 victory, Milan's first away win of 2015. M\u00e9nez's season, however, ended poorly; on 29 April 2015, he was sent off for a second bookable offensive during the 3\u20131 defeat against [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] and was handed a four-match ban for an insulting gesture, also missing the team's last match against [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] due to an injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/ac-milan/story/2427756/ac-milans-jeremy-menez-receives-four-match-ban|title=AC Milan's Jeremy Menez receives four-match ban for 'insulting gestures'}}</ref> M\u00e9nez ended his first season at Milan as the club's top scorer, with 34 appearances and 16 goals in all competitions.\n\nIn the subsequent summer, M\u00e9nez suffered back problems and underwent surgery in [[Monaco]]. On 21 August, he was ruled out for a month as further back complications arose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/71360/milan-lose-menez-month|title=Milan lose Menez for a month \u2013 Football Italia|publisher=football-italia.net}}</ref> An infection meant he missed the first 26 games of the [[2015\u201316 A.C. Milan season|2015\u201316 season]] and was kept from playing until his return in a 2\u20131 [[2015\u201316 Serie A|league]] win over Genoa on 14 February 2016. On 1 March, he started a match for the first time since April 2015, playing 76 minutes and scoring twice in a 5\u20130 [[Coppa Italia]] defeat of [[U.S. Alessandria Calcio 1912|Alessandria]], sending Milan to the [[2016 Coppa Italia Final|final]] for the first time since [[2003 Coppa Italia Final|2003]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11854/10188919/jeremy-menez-thanks-ac-milan-after-a-two-goal-haul-on-tuesday|title=Jeremy Menez thanks AC Milan after a two-goal haul on Tuesday}}</ref>\n\n===Bordeaux===\nOn 1 August 2016, Bordeaux and Milan reached an agreement for the transfer of M\u00e9nez.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.girondins.com/en/menez-deal-reached-ac-milan.html|title=M\u00e9nez \u2013 Deal reached with AC Milan|publisher=FC Girondins de Bordeaux|date=1 August 2016|accessdate=1 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806185337/http://www.girondins.com/en/menez-deal-reached-ac-milan.html|archivedate=6 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 3 August, two days after signing for the club, he was involved in a gruesome incident in a pre-season match against Lorient. The injury occurred in the second-half when Lorient midfielder [[Didier Ibrahim N'Dong|Didier Ndong]] inadvertently stood on M\u00e9nez's head, causing the former French international to lose part of his right ear in the process. M\u00e9nez had only come on as a substitute in the 62nd minute but had to be taken off a little more than 15 minutes later when the incident happened. Ndong offered his apologies to M\u00e9nez for his part in the accident, stating, \"I offer my apologies to Jeremy M\u00e9nez and Girondins de Bordeaux. I give him my full support for the coming days and hope to see him very quickly on the pitches of Ligue 1.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3722599/Jeremy-Menez-endures-debut-hell-Bordeaux-ear-ripped-against-Lorient.html|title=Jeremy Menez endures the debut from hell for Bordeaux as part of his ear is ripped off against Lorient|work=Daily Mail|first=James|last=Dutton|date=3 August 2016|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/news/menez-loses-part-ear-horror-injury-debut|title=Menez loses part of ear in horror injury on debut|publisher=FourFourTwo|date=4 August 2016|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Antalyaspor===\nOn 9 June 2017, he joined the Turkish club [[Antalyaspor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/3141298/jeremy-menezs-move-from-bordeaux-to-turkish-club-antalyaspor-agreed|title=Jeremy Menez's move from Bordeaux to Turkish club Antalyaspor agreed|publisher=ESPN|date=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Am\u00e9rica===\nOn 5 January 2018, it was announced M\u00e9nez had joined Mexican side [[Club Am\u00e9rica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/3336727/jeremy-menez-completes-transfer-to-club-america-in-mexico|title=Jeremy Menez completes transfer to Club America in Mexico|publisher=ESPN|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> He made his [[Liga MX]] debut on 27 January against [[Club Atlas|Atlas]]. He appeared as a substitute in the 67th minute for [[Cecilio Dom\u00ednguez]] in Am\u00e9rica's 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cr\u00f3nica Am\u00e9rica 1-0 Atlas Jornada 4|url=https://www.clubamerica.com.mx/comunicados/cronica-america-1-0-atlas-jornada-4/ |website=clubamerica.com.mx |publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica |language=Spanish |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> The following week, M\u00e9nez scored his first goal for Am\u00e9rica in a 5\u20131 against [[Lobos BUAP]].<ref>https://www.univision.com/deportes/futbol/liga-mx/america-goleo-a-lobos-buap-en-la-jornada-5-del-clausura-2018-de-la-liga-mx</ref>\nOn 10 February, he scored from the penalty spot to equalize the score in Am\u00e9rica's 1\u20131 draw against [[Tigres UANL]]. On 2 May, he scored two penaltys against [[Pumas UNAM]] in the quarterfinals away match, which Am\u00e9rica would later win 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laaficion.milenio.com/futbol/jeremy-menez-mateus-uribe-humillan-pumas-cu-club-america-liguilla-resultado_0_1168083607.html|title=J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez y Mateus Uribe humillan a Pumas en CU|publisher=Milenio|date=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August, during a friendly match against [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]], he suffered an [[anterior cruciate ligament injury]] ruling him out between 6 and 9 months, leaving him out of the [[2019-20 Liga MX season#Torneo Apertura|2019 Torneo Apertura]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Club America's Jeremy Menez ruled out of Apertura with ligament injury|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/america/story/3559958/club-americas-jeremy-menez-ruled-out-of-apertura-with-ligament-injury|work=ESPN|first=Tom|last=Marshall|date=8 July 2018|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2019, it was announced that M\u00e9nez and [[Club Am\u00e9rica]] ended their contractual relation on a mutual agreement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oficial: J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez se va del Am\u00e9rica|url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/liga-mx/2019/08/29/5d67ef6fca4741db528b4609.html |website=marca.com |publisher=Marca |language=Spanish |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Paris FC===\nOn 27 September 2019, he signed a one-year contract with French club [[Paris FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parisfc.fr/equipe-pro/jeremy-menez-sengage-avec-le-paris-fc/|title=J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez s\u2019engage avec le Paris FC|accessdate=26 September 2019|date=26 September 2019|publisher=[[Paris FC]]|language=French}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\nM\u00e9nez has earned caps with all of [[France national youth football team|France's youth teams]]. He is a member of the group, commonly known as the ''G\u00e9n\u00e9ration 1987'', that produced current internationals [[Hatem Ben Arfa]], [[Karim Benzema]] and [[Samir Nasri]], alongside himself. M\u00e9nez made his youth international debut with the [[France national under-16 football team|under-16 team]] on 11 December 2002 in a [[Exhibition match|friendly match]] against [[Greece national football team|Greece]], playing alongside Nasri and Ben Arfa. In the match, M\u00e9nez scored the fifth goal of a 6\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/40021.shtml | title = La France termine l'ann\u00e9e en beaut\u00e9 face \u00e0 la Gr\u00e8ce (6\u20131) |date= 11 December 2002 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At the 2003 Aegean Cup in Turkey, he scored goals in three consecutive matches. M\u00e9nez scored goals against the [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] and [[Israel national football team|Israel]] and netted his final goal in the third-place match against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/41839.shtml | title = La France se reprend face \u00e0 Isra\u00ebl (3\u20131) |date= 8 January 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/42113.shtml | title = Les tricolores dominent l'Ukraine (5\u20130) |date= 10 January 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/42275.shtml | title = La France termine troisi\u00e8me (3\u20132) |date= 12 January 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Montaigu Tournament|Tournio de Montaigu]], M\u00e9nez scored three goals, second-best on the team behind Ben Arfa. He scored a goal in the team's 8\u20130 win over [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]] in the team's opening group match and, in the following match, scored the opening goal in the team's 3\u20130 win over [[Russia national football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/51364.shtml | title = Entr\u00e9e en mati\u00e8re r\u00e9ussie face au Gabon (8\u20130) |date= 16 April 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/51476.shtml | title = La France poursuit sur sa lanc\u00e9e (3\u20130) |date= 17 April 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> In the team's final group stage match against [[England national under-16 football team|England]], M\u00e9nez netted another goal in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/51666.shtml | title = La France gagne (3\u20131) et se retrouve en finale! |date= 19 April 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At a regional tournament in [[Salerno]], Italy, M\u00e9nez led the team to the title by scoring a double in the final match against [[Italy national football team|the hosts]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/56535.shtml | title = La France victorieuse \u00e0 Salerne! |date= 19 June 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> He also scored two goals in the group matches against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/54633.shtml | title = Les Tricolores d\u00e9butent bien face au Japon (3\u20132) |date= 15 June 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/56205.shtml | title = La France bat la Finlande (3\u20131) |date= 17 June 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> M\u00e9nez finished the under-16 campaign with 14 appearances and a team-leading 12 goals.\n\nWith the [[France national under-17 football team|under-17 team]], M\u00e9nez, Ben Arfa, and Nasri were joined by Karim Benzema and tasked with the goal of winning the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship]] on home soil. M\u00e9nez made his debut with the team in the opening match of the season against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]. In the Tournio de [[Val-de-Marne]], he scored one goal. France were crowned champions without conceding a goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m17ans/actualite/72264.shtml | title = Philippe Bergeroo : \"Un tournoi riche d'enseignements\" |date= 1 November 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At the 2004 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship, M\u00e9nez contributed to the team's winning the competition by scoring two goals, netting one against [[Turkey national under-17 football team|Turkey]] in the group stage and a second in the semi-finals against [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75060/index.html |title=France lifted by late goals |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=16 June 2010 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831172349/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1658/match%3D75060/index.html |archivedate=31 August 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75064/index.html |title=Flamboyant hosts earn final chance |date=9 May 2004 |accessdate=16 June 2010 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115024746/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1658/match%3D75064/index.html |archivedate=15 January 2016 }}</ref> In total with the under-17s, he made 17 appearances and scored 6 goals. Due to increased playing time at his parent club Sochaux, M\u00e9nez's stint with the [[France national under-18 football team|under-18 team]] was uneventful. M\u00e9nez did appear with the team at the [[2005 UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup|2005 Meridian Cup]], scoring five goals in four matches as France were crowned champions.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html |title=2005: Europe extend Meridian domination |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=26 April 2011 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721123909/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html |archivedate=21 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe foursome of Ben Arfa, Nasri, Benzema and M\u00e9nez returned to international play together for [[France national under-19 football team|under-19]] duty. The four were joined by [[Issiar Dia]], Blaise Matuidi and [[Serge Gakp\u00e9]] with the objective of winning the [[2006 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]]. In the first round of qualification for the tournament, M\u00e9nez went scoreless as France advanced through the round undefeated. In the final round of qualification, he scored a double against [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]] in a 4\u20130 win. Despite finishing the round undefeated, however, France were eliminated after being beaten on points by [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland]].\n\nM\u00e9nez was absent from the [[France national under-21 football team|under-21]] team during his early eligibility term but made his debut on 25 May 2008 in the team's 2\u20131 friendly match win over the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]]. He went months without a call-up before finally returning to the team ahead of the important two-legged playoff against [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in qualification for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]] in October 2008. M\u00e9nez appeared in both legs as France were defeated 2\u20131 on aggregate. The 1\u20130 loss in the second leg eliminated France from the competition and also ended M\u00e9nez's under-21 career.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=41 | title = France v. Germany Match Report |date= 15 October 2008 | accessdate =7 January 2011 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref>\n\n[[File:J.M\u00e9nez Euro 2012.jpg|thumb|250px|right|M\u00e9nez (right) playing for [[France national football team|France]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] at [[UEFA Euro 2012]].]]\n\n===Senior===\nOn 5 August 2010, M\u00e9nez was called up to the [[France national football team|senior team]] for the first time by new manager [[Laurent Blanc]] for the team's [[Exhibition match|friendly match]] against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] on 11 August 2010.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/aug/05/karim-benzema-hatem-ben-arfa-france | title = Karim Benzema and Hatem Ben Arfa in Laurent Blanc's first France squad | date = 5 August 2010 | work=[[Guardian Media Group]] | accessdate =21 February 2011 }}</ref> He made his international debut in the match starting on the right wing as France were defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1285 | title = 11/08/2010 Equipe de France A \u2013 Amical  |date= 11 August 2010 | accessdate =23 February 2011 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> On 9 February 2011, M\u00e9nez assisted on the only goal, scored by Karim Benzema, in the team's 1\u20130 win over [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[Stade de France]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/international-friendlies/8315057/France-1-Brazil-0-match-report.html | title = France 1 Brazil 0: match report |date= 9 February 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref> After appearing regularly in [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|qualifying]] for [[UEFA Euro 2012]], on 29 May 2012, M\u00e9nez was named to the squad to participate in the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/yoann-gourcuff-omitted-as-france-announce-euro-2012-squad-7800136.html|title=Yoann Gourcuff omitted as France announce Euro 2012 squad|date=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=3 June 2012 }}</ref> On 5 June, in the team's final warm-up friendly ahead of the Euro, he scored his first international goal in a 4\u20130 shutout win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605,0,7372040.story|title=Benzema, Ribery shine as France thrash Estonia|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130102044447/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-06-05/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605_1_estonia-karim-benzema-laurent-blanc|archive-date=2 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At Euro 2012, M\u00e9nez made his debut at a senior international competition on 15 June in the team's second group stage match against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]. In the contest, he started and scored France's opening goal in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/16/sports/soccer/euro-2012-after-rain-delay-france-shuts-out-ukraine.html|title=After Rain Delay, France Shuts Out Ukraine|work=[[The New York Times]] |date= 15 June 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|2 May 2018}}<ref name=uc0405/><ref name=ligue1>{{cite web|title=J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez profile|url=http://www.ligue1.com/joueur/menez-jeremy|publisher=Ligue 1}}</ref><ref name=sw>{{Soccerway|jeremy-menez/1516}}</ref>\n\nUpdated 21 April 2020.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Club performance\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=140|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|France \u2013 [[Coupe de France]]; Italy \u2013 [[Coppa Italia]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|France \u2013 [[Coupe de la Ligue]]}}\n!colspan=2|Continental \n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!width=40|Apps!!width=40|Goals\n!width=45|Apps!!width=45|Goals\n!width=45|Apps!!width=45|Goals\n!width=40|Apps!!width=40|Goals\n!width=40|Apps!!width=40|Goals\n!width=40|Apps!!width=40|Goa